{"title_page": "Yukito Ayatsuji", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name       = Yukito Ayatsuji\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| pseudonym  = Yukito Ayatsuji\n| birth_name = Naoyuki Uchida\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1960|12|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Kyoto]], Japan\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = Writer\n| language   = Japanese\n| period     = 1987\u2013present\n| genre      = [[Whodunit]], [[Closed circle of suspects|closed circle mystery]], [[mystery fiction]], [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]], [[Horror fiction|horror]]\n| movement   = The new traditionalist movement\n| website    = \n| spouse     = [[Fuyumi Ono]]\n| children   =\n| awards     = [[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]] (1992)\n| Siblings   = \n| signature  = Ayatsuji Yukito signature.png\n}}\n{{Japanese name|[[Ayatsuji]]}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Naoyuki Uchida'''|\u5185\u7530 \u76f4\u884c|Uchida Naoyuki|extra=born December 23, 1960}}, who writes under his pen name {{nihongo|'''Yukito Ayatsuji'''|\u7dbe\u8fbb \u884c\u4eba|Ayatsuji Yukito}}, is a Japanese writer of [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] and [[Horror fiction|horror]]. He is one of the founders of [[Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan]] and one of the representative writers of the new traditionalist movement in Japanese mystery writing.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/date.html#pageLink01|script-title=ja:\u672c\u683c\u30df\u30b9\u30c6\u30ea\u4f5c\u5bb6\u30af\u30e9\u30d6\uff08\u6e96\u5099\u4f1a\uff09\u8a2d\u7acb\u306b\u5bc4\u305b\u3066|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last = Wong|first = Ho-Ling|url= http://www.criminalelement.com/blogs/2011/05/ellery-queen-is-alive-and-well-and-living-in-japan|title= Ellery Queen is Alive and Well and Living in Japan|publisher= Criminal Element|accessdate=November 11, 2013}}</ref> His wife is [[Fuyumi Ono]], a Japanese [[fantasy]] and horror writer who is known for her fantasy series ''[[The Twelve Kingdoms]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/227-yukito-ayatsuji|title= Yukito Ayatsuji, Books from Japan|publisher= J-Lit Center|accessdate=November 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis first novel ''[[The Decagon House Murders]]'' was ranked as the No. 8 novel on the [[Tozai Mystery Best 100|Top 100 Japanese Mystery Novels of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://ebookstore.sony.jp/stc/special/news/tozaimystery_j/index.html|title= Tozai Mystery Best 100 (Revised Edition 2012), The Top 50 Japanese Mystery Novels|publisher= Reader Store|accessdate=November 11, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a minor planet (2001 RG46) was named as Yukito Ayatsuji.<ref>{{cite web |title=55212 Yukitoayatsuji (2001 RG46) |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=55212#content |website=JPL Small-Body Database Browser |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n;Another series\n* ''[[Another (novel)|Another]]'',  translated by Karen McGillicuddy ([[Yen Press]], 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yenpress.com/another-novel/|title=Another (novel) by Yukito Ayatsuji|publisher=[[Yen Press]]|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''Another Episode S / 0'',  translated by Karen McGillicuddy (Yen Press, 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/yukito-ayatsuji/another-episode-s-0/9780316312318/?yen|title=Another Episode S / 0|publisher=Yen Press|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Bizarre House/Mansion Murders series\n* ''[[The Decagon House Murders]]'' (original title: ''Jukkakukan no Satsujin''), translated by Ho-Ling Wong (Locked Room International, 2015)\n\n;Short story\n* ''Heart of Darkness'' (original title: ''Kokoro no Yami''),  translated by Daniel Jackson (''Speculative Japan 3: Silver Bullet and Other Tales of Japanese Science Fiction and Fantasy'', Kurodahan Press, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurodahan.com/mt/e/catalog/jp0024cate.html|title=Speculative Japan 3|publisher=Kurodahan Press|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Essay\n* ''My Favourite Mystery, \"Farewell, My Mask\" by [[Akimitsu Takagi]]'' ([[Mystery Writers of Japan|Mystery Writers of Japan, Inc.]] [http://www.mystery.or.jp/en/column.html?id=favorite-5])\n\nHis first novel ''The Decagon House Murders'' is available in French translation under the title ''Meurtres dans le decagone'' ({{ISBN|2-9533-9621-7}}).<ref>{{cite journal|title = AYATSUJI Yukito, la tradition a du bon|journal = Zoom Japon|volume = 1|pages = 7|date = June 2010|language=French|url= http://www.zoomjapon.info/pdf/mag/ZOOM_Japon-001.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* 1992 \u2013 [[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]] for Best Novel: ''Tokeikan no Satsujin'' (''Clock Mansion Murders'')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://db2.dcube.co.jp/mystery/FMPro?-db=mystery_sakuhin.fp5&-format=prize_detail.html&-lay=cgi&-error=prize_detail.html&-Op=eq&w_kai==45&w_sho==1&%8D%EC%95i==%8E%9E%8Cv%8A%D9%82%CC%8EE%90l&-max=1&-Find|title= 1992 (45th) Mystery Writers of Japan Award for Best Novel|publisher= Mystery Writers of Japan, Inc.|accessdate=November 11, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 Nominee for [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] for Best Fiction: ''Ankokukan no Satsujin'' (''Dark Mansion Murders'')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/taishou2005.html|title= 5th (2005) Honkaku Mystery Award|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 Nominee for [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] for Best Fiction: ''[[Another (novel)|Another]]''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/taishou2010.html|title= 10th (2010) Honkaku Mystery Award|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/english.html|title= The Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=English}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Bizarre House/Mansion Murders series===\n* {{nihongo|''Jukkakukan no Satsujin''|\u5341\u89d2\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1987 (''The Decagon House Murders''. Locked Room International. 2015)\n* {{nihongo|''Suishakan no Satsujin''|\u6c34\u8eca\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1988 (''The Water Mill Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Meirokan no Satsujin''|\u8ff7\u8def\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1988 (''The Labyrinth Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Ningy\u014dkan no Satsujin''|\u4eba\u5f62\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1989 (''The Doll Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Tokeikan no Satsujin''|\u6642\u8a08\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1991 (''The Clock Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Kuronekokan no Satsujin''|\u9ed2\u732b\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1992 (''The Black Cat Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Ankokukan no Satsujin''|\u6697\u9ed2\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 2004 (''The Dark Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Bikkurikan no Satsujin''|\u3073\u3063\u304f\u308a\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 2006 (''The Surprise Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Kimenkan no Satsujin''|\u5947\u9762\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 2012 (''The Queer Mask Mansion Murders'')\n\n===Whispering series===\n* {{nihongo|''Hiiro no Sasayaki''|\u7dcb\u8272\u306e\u56c1\u304d|}}, 1988 (''The Scarlet Whispering'')\n* {{nihongo|''Kurayami no Sasayaki''|\u6697\u95c7\u306e\u56c1\u304d|}}, 1989 (''The Darkness Whispering'')\n* {{nihongo|''Tasogare no Sasayaki''|\u9ec4\u660f\u306e\u56c1\u304d|}}, 1993 (''The Twilight Whispering'')\n\n===Equation of Murder series===\n* {{nihongo|''Satsujin H\u014dteishiki: Setsudansareta Shitai no Mondai''|\u6bba\u4eba\u65b9\u7a0b\u5f0f \u5207\u65ad\u3055\u308c\u305f\u6b7b\u4f53\u306e\u554f\u984c|}}, 1989\n* {{nihongo|''Satsujin H\u014dteishiki 2: Meif\u016bs\u014d Jiken''|\u6bba\u4eba\u65b9\u7a0b\u5f0fII \u9cf4\u98a8\u8358\u4e8b\u4ef6|}}, 1995\n\n===Blood Thirsty Killer series===\n* {{nihongo|''Satsujinki: Kakusei-hen''|\u6bba\u4eba\u9b3c \u899a\u9192\u7bc7|}}, 1990\n* {{nihongo|''Satsujinki: Gyakush\u016b-hen''|\u6bba\u4eba\u9b3c \u9006\u8972\u7bc7|}}, 1993\n\n===Horror Stories of Midorogaoka series===\n* {{nihongo|''Midorogaoka Kidan''|\u6df1\u6ce5\u4e18\u5947\u8ac7|}}, 2008\n* {{nihongo|''Midorogaoka Kidan Zoku''|\u6df1\u6ce5\u4e18\u5947\u8ac7\u30fb\u7d9a|}}, 2011\n** {{nihongo|''Suzu''|\u9234|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Konekomegani''|\u30b3\u30cd\u30b3\u30e1\u30ac\u30cb|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Kurui-Zakura''|\u72c2\u3044\u685c|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Kokoro no Yami''|\u5fc3\u306e\u95c7|}} (''Heart of Darkness'')\n** {{nihongo|''Ho wa Hor\u0101 Eiga no Ho''|\u30db\u306f\u30db\u30e9\u30fc\u6620\u753b\u306e\u30db|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Midorogaoka San Jiz\u014d''|\u6df1\u6ce5\u4e18\u4e09\u5730\u8535|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Sou''|\u30bd\u30a6|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Setsudan''|\u5207\u65ad|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Yoru Ugomeku''|\u591c\u8822\u304f|}}\n** {{nihongo|''Rajio T\u014d''|\u30e9\u30b8\u30aa\u5854|}}\n\n===Another series===\n* ''[[Another (novel)|Another]]'', 2009\n* {{nihongo|''Another: Episode S''|Another \u30a8\u30d4\u30bd\u30fc\u30c9S|Anaz\u0101 Episodo Esu}}, 2013\n\n===Standalone novels===\n* {{nihongo|''Kirigoetei Satsujin Jiken''|\u9727\u8d8a\u90b8\u6bba\u4eba\u4e8b\u4ef6|}}, 1990\n* {{nihongo|''Saigo no Kioku''|\u6700\u5f8c\u306e\u8a18\u61b6|}}, 2002\n\n===Short story collections===\n* {{nihongo|''Ganky\u016b Kitan''|\u773c\u7403\u7dba\u8b5a|}}, 1995\n* {{nihongo|''Freaks''|\u30d5\u30ea\u30fc\u30af\u30b9|Fur\u012bkusu}}, 1996\n* {{nihongo|''Dondon-Bashi, Ochita''|\u3069\u3093\u3069\u3093\u6a4b\u3001\u843d\u3061\u305f|}}, 1999\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Novels|Japan}}\n{{Wikipedia books|Another (novel)|''Another'' (novel)}}\n*[[Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan]]\n*[[Japanese detective fiction]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://twitter.com/ayatsujiyukito Twitter]\n\n{{Fuyumi Ono}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayatsuji, Yukito}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese novelists]]\n[[Category:Japanese male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Japanese horror writers]]\n[[Category:Mystery Writers of Japan Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Kyoto]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese short story writers]]\n[[Category:Male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name       = Yukito Ayatsuji\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| pseudonym  = Yukito Ayatsuji\n| birth_name = Naoyuki Uchida\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1960|12|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Kyoto]], Japan\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = Writer\n| language   = Japanese\n| period     = 1987\u2013present\n| genre      = [[Whodunit]], [[Closed circle of suspects|closed circle mystery]], [[mystery fiction]], [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]], [[Horror fiction|horror]]\n| movement   = The new traditionalist movement\n| website    = \n| spouse     = [[Fuyumi Ono]]\n| children   =\n| awards     = [[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]] (1992)\n| Siblings   = \n| signature  =\n}}\n{{Japanese name|[[Ayatsuji]]}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Naoyuki Uchida'''|\u5185\u7530 \u76f4\u884c|Uchida Naoyuki|extra=born December 23, 1960}}, who writes under his pen name {{nihongo|'''Yukito Ayatsuji'''|\u7dbe\u8fbb \u884c\u4eba|Ayatsuji Yukito}}, is a Japanese writer of [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] and [[Horror fiction|horror]]. He is one of the founders of [[Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan]] and one of the representative writers of the new traditionalist movement in Japanese mystery writing.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/date.html#pageLink01|script-title=ja:\u672c\u683c\u30df\u30b9\u30c6\u30ea\u4f5c\u5bb6\u30af\u30e9\u30d6\uff08\u6e96\u5099\u4f1a\uff09\u8a2d\u7acb\u306b\u5bc4\u305b\u3066|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last = Wong|first = Ho-Ling|url= http://www.criminalelement.com/blogs/2011/05/ellery-queen-is-alive-and-well-and-living-in-japan|title= Ellery Queen is Alive and Well and Living in Japan|publisher= Criminal Element|accessdate=November 11, 2013}}</ref> His wife is [[Fuyumi Ono]], a Japanese [[fantasy]] and horror writer who is known for her fantasy series ''[[The Twelve Kingdoms]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.booksfromjapan.jp/authors/item/227-yukito-ayatsuji|title= Yukito Ayatsuji, Books from Japan|publisher= J-Lit Center|accessdate=November 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis first novel ''[[The Decagon House Murders]]'' was ranked as the No. 8 novel on the [[Tozai Mystery Best 100|Top 100 Japanese Mystery Novels of All Time]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://ebookstore.sony.jp/stc/special/news/tozaimystery_j/index.html|title= Tozai Mystery Best 100 (Revised Edition 2012), The Top 50 Japanese Mystery Novels|publisher= Reader Store|accessdate=November 11, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a minor planet (2001 RG46) was named as Yukito Ayatsuji.<ref>{{cite web |title=55212 Yukitoayatsuji (2001 RG46) |url=https://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=55212#content |website=JPL Small-Body Database Browser |accessdate=18 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Translations==\n;Another series\n* ''[[Another (novel)|Another]]'',  translated by Karen McGillicuddy ([[Yen Press]], 2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yenpress.com/another-novel/|title=Another (novel) by Yukito Ayatsuji|publisher=[[Yen Press]]|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>\n* ''Another Episode S / 0'',  translated by Karen McGillicuddy (Yen Press, 2016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/yukito-ayatsuji/another-episode-s-0/9780316312318/?yen|title=Another Episode S / 0|publisher=Yen Press|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Bizarre House/Mansion Murders series\n* ''[[The Decagon House Murders]]'' (original title: ''Jukkakukan no Satsujin''), translated by Ho-Ling Wong (Locked Room International, 2015)\n\n;Short story\n* ''Heart of Darkness'' (original title: ''Kokoro no Yami''),  translated by Daniel Jackson (''Speculative Japan 3: Silver Bullet and Other Tales of Japanese Science Fiction and Fantasy'', Kurodahan Press, 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kurodahan.com/mt/e/catalog/jp0024cate.html|title=Speculative Japan 3|publisher=Kurodahan Press|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Essay\n* ''My Favourite Mystery, \"Farewell, My Mask\" by [[Akimitsu Takagi]]'' ([[Mystery Writers of Japan|Mystery Writers of Japan, Inc.]] [http://www.mystery.or.jp/en/column.html?id=favorite-5])\n\nHis first novel ''The Decagon House Murders'' is available in French translation under the title ''Meurtres dans le decagone'' ({{ISBN|2-9533-9621-7}}).<ref>{{cite journal|title = AYATSUJI Yukito, la tradition a du bon|journal = Zoom Japon|volume = 1|pages = 7|date = June 2010|language=French|url= http://www.zoomjapon.info/pdf/mag/ZOOM_Japon-001.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n* 1992 \u2013 [[Mystery Writers of Japan Award]] for Best Novel: ''Tokeikan no Satsujin'' (''Clock Mansion Murders'')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://db2.dcube.co.jp/mystery/FMPro?-db=mystery_sakuhin.fp5&-format=prize_detail.html&-lay=cgi&-error=prize_detail.html&-Op=eq&w_kai==45&w_sho==1&%8D%EC%95i==%8E%9E%8Cv%8A%D9%82%CC%8EE%90l&-max=1&-Find|title= 1992 (45th) Mystery Writers of Japan Award for Best Novel|publisher= Mystery Writers of Japan, Inc.|accessdate=November 11, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 Nominee for [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] for Best Fiction: ''Ankokukan no Satsujin'' (''Dark Mansion Murders'')<ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/taishou2005.html|title= 5th (2005) Honkaku Mystery Award|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 Nominee for [[Honkaku Mystery Award]] for Best Fiction: ''[[Another (novel)|Another]]''<ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/taishou2010.html|title= 10th (2010) Honkaku Mystery Award|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://honkaku.com/english.html|title= The Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|publisher= Honkaku Mystery Writers Club of Japan|accessdate=July 16, 2015|language=English}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Bizarre House/Mansion Murders series===\n* {{nihongo|''Jukkakukan no Satsujin''|\u5341\u89d2\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1987 (''The Decagon House Murders''. Locked Room International. 2015)\n* {{nihongo|''Suishakan no Satsujin''|\u6c34\u8eca\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1988 (''The Water Mill Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Meirokan no Satsujin''|\u8ff7\u8def\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1988 (''The Labyrinth Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Ningy\u014dkan no Satsujin''|\u4eba\u5f62\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1989 (''The Doll Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Tokeikan no Satsujin''|\u6642\u8a08\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1991 (''The Clock Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Kuronekokan no Satsujin''|\u9ed2\u732b\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 1992 (''The Black Cat Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Ankokukan no Satsujin''|\u6697\u9ed2\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 2004 (''The Dark Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Bikkurikan no Satsujin''|\u3073\u3063\u304f\u308a\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 2006 (''The Surprise Mansion Murders'')\n* {{nihongo|''Kimenkan no Satsujin''|\u5947\u9762\u9928\u306e\u6bba\u4eba|}}, 2012 (''The Queer Mask Mansion Murders'')\n\n===Whispering series===\n* {{nihongo|''Hiiro no Sasayaki''|\u7dcb\u8272\u306e\u56c1\u304d|}}, 1988 (''The Scarlet Whispering'')\n* {{nihongo|''Kurayami no Sasayaki''|\u6697\u95c7\u306e\u56c1\u304d|}}, 1989 (''The Darkness Whisperi