2011\n| [[32nd Young Artist Awards]]\n| {{nom}}\n| <center><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms32.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808150433/http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms32.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 August 2013|title=32nd Annual Young Artist Awards - Nominations / Special Awards|date=8 August 2013|accessdate=30 March 2018}}</ref></center>\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[34th Young Artist Awards]]\n| [[Young Artist Award for Best Leading Young Actress in a Feature Film|Best Performance in a Feature Film - Leading Young Actress]]\n| ''[[Paranormal Activity 4]]''\n| {{won}}\n| <center><ref name=\"Young Artist Awards 3\"/></center>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1105980}}\n* {{Instagram|kathrynnewton}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newton, Kathryn}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame High School (Sherman Oaks, California) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "48Pills", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathryn_Newton"}
{"title_page": "Area codes 778, 236, and 672", "text_new": "{{short description|Overlay area codes for British Columbia, Canada}}\n'''Area codes 778, 236, and 672''' are [[Overlay plan|overlay]] [[area code]]s for the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Canadian province]] of [[British Columbia]]. They overlay the existing area codes, [[area code 604|604]] and [[area code 250|250]], simultaneously, requiring [[ten-digit dialling]] throughout the province. The area codes also serve the United States community of [[Hyder, Alaska]], which sits along the [[Canada\u2013United States border]] near the town of [[Stewart, British Columbia|Stewart]].\n\n==History==\nArea code 604 had served as British Columbia's sole area code for 53 years before 250 was created as the area code for [[Vancouver Island]] and the [[British Columbia Interior|Interior]] in 1997, with 604 cut back to serve [[Vancouver]] and the [[Lower Mainland]]. This was intended as a long-term solution; however, within four years, 604 was on the brink of exhaustion once again due to Canada's number allocation system. Every [[competitive local exchange carrier]] is allocated blocks of 10,000 numbers\u2014corresponding to a single prefix\u2014for every rate centre where they plan to offer service, even in the smallest hamlets. While most rate centres do not need nearly that many numbers, a number cannot be allocated elsewhere once assigned to a rate centre and carrier.  \n\nWhile numbers tended to be used up fairly quickly in the immediate Vancouver area due to its rapid growth, the number allocation problem was particularly severe in the Lower Mainland. It is home to most of the province's landlines and cell phones. \n\nTo solve this problem, area code 778 was created on November 3, 2001, as a concentrated overlay for the two largest [[list of regional districts of British Columbia|regional districts]] in the Lower Mainland, [[Metro Vancouver]] and the [[Fraser Valley Regional District]]. The rest of the Lower Mainland continued to use only 604.<ref>[http://www.nanpa.com/pdf/pl-nanp-246.pdf NANP Planning Letter PL-246]</ref> Nonetheless, the implementation of 778 made [[10-digit dialing]] mandatory across the Lower Mainland.\n\nIn early 2007, the [[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]] (CRTC) faced the prospect that 250 would exhaust in early 2008. Relief proposals included:<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/pt2007-2.htm |title=New dialing to come in British Columbia |access-date=May 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090629062145/http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/pt2007-2.htm |archive-date=June 29, 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\n* a geographic split that would have seen the Interior retain 250, with Vancouver Island switching to a new area code\n* expanding 778 to the 250 territory\n* concentrated overlays covering part of the 250 territory\n\nUltimately, the CRTC concluded that there was not enough time to implement a split before 250 was due to exhaust. Additionally, the major landline and cell phone providers in the 250 territory contended that an overlay would be far easier to implement than a split. [[Telus]] and other carriers wanted to spare their Vancouver Island customers the expense and burden of changing their numbers for the second time in a decade.<ref name=CRTC>[https://crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/dt2007-38.pdf Telecom Decision 2007-38]</ref>  \n\nAccordingly, the CRTC announced on June 7, 2007, that 778 would become an overlay for the entire province effective July 4, 2007.<ref>[http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/NEWS/RELEASES/2007/r070607.htm New dialing to come in British Columbia] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090626081224/http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/NEWS/RELEASES/2007/r070607.htm |date=June 26, 2009 }}</ref>  Overlays have become the preferred method of relief in Canada, as they are an easy workaround for the number allocation problem; no area codes have been split in the country since 1999.\n\nAs of June 23, 2008, ten-digit dialling became mandatory across British Columbia; attempting to use seven digits would trigger an [[intercept message]] reminding callers of the new rule. After September 12, 2008, seven-digit dialling ceased to function.<ref>[http://www.ctvbc.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20080622/BC_Ten_Digit_Dialing_080622/20080622/?hub=BritishColumbiaHome Ten-digit dialing coming to all of B.C.]</ref>\n\nThis was intended as a long-term solution, but within four years 604, 250 and 778 were close to exhaustion once again. To solve the problem, area code 236 went into effect as an additional overlay for the province on June 1, 2013.<ref name=\"crtc2011451\">{{cite web|title=Telecom Decision CRTC 2011-451|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2011/2011-451.htm|publisher=[[Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission]]|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nArea codes 604, 250, 778 and 236 are expected to be exhausted by May 2020. As such, the CRTC has ordered the introduction of a third overlay for the province, 672, which was put into effect on May 4, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2018/2018-58.htm|title=Relief for area codes 236, 250, 604, and 778 in British Columbia|last=(CRTC)|first=Government of Canada, Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission|website=crtc.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2018-02-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=B.C. is getting a new area code next year |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-area-codes-new-1.4535413 |date=February 14, 2018 |work=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Communities included==\n\n*[[Abbotsford, British Columbia|Abbotsford]] (778) \u2013 201 314 344 345 360 761 769 771 779 780 856 880 982\n*[[Aldergrove, British Columbia|Aldergrove]] (236) \u2013 260; (778) \u2013 240 241 242 243 245 246 255 369 549 551 552 556 808 809 823 825  878 908\n*[[Campbell River, British Columbia|Campbell River]]