=Notes and references==\n<!-- These ones were just grabbed from both 250 and 604 -->\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{cite journal|last=Fabisch|first=M.P.|journal=Bellcore Letter|url=http://www.nanpa.com/pdf/old_pl/IL%2095-08-007.pdf |title=NANP-Split of 604 (British Columbia) Numbering Plan Area (NPA)|date=1995-08-17 |accessdate=2007-01-24}}\n* {{cite journal |author=Suresh Khare |title=Planning Document NPA 250 Numbering Relief |version=1.0 |publisher=Canadian Numbering Administrator (CNA) |date=October 26, 2006 |url=http://www.cnac.ca/npa_codes/relief/completed/250/NPA250_PD_26_Oct_2006_rev_1.pdf |accessdate=2012-07-19}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- These ones were just grabbed from both 250 and 604 -->\n* [http://www.nanpa.com/pdf/pl-nanp-246.pdf NANP Planning Letter PL-246]\n* [http://www.cnac.ca/data/COCodeStatus_NPA236.htm CNA exchange list for area +1-236]\n* [http://www.cnac.ca/data/COCodeStatus_NPA672.htm CNA exchange list for area +1-672]\n* [http://www.cnac.ca/data/COCodeStatus_NPA778.htm CNA exchange list for area +1-778]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060813195028/http://www.cnac.ca/npa_codes/relief/250/relief_250.htm CNA NPA 250 Relief Planning]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040325174047/http://mirror.lcs.mit.edu/telecom-archives/archives/history/56th-anniversary-areacodes Telecom archives]\n* [http://www.cnac.ca/area_code_maps/canadian_area_codes.htm Area Code Map of Canada]\n\n{{Area code box| State = BC\n| This = 778, 236, and 672 (overlaid with [[Area code 250|250]] and [[Area code 604|604]])\n| N = [[Area code 867|867]]\n| S = [[Area code 360|360]]/[[Area code 564|564]], [[Area code 509|509]], [[Area codes 208 and 986|208/986]], [[Area code 406|406]]\n| E = [[Area code 780|780]], [[Area code 403|403]], [[Area codes 587 and 825|587]]/[[Area codes 587 and 825|825 (overlay)]]\n| W = [[Pacific Ocean]], [[Area code 907|907]]\n|S1=AB|S2=YT|S3=ID|S4=WA|S5=AK}}\n\n{{coord|54|N|124|W|region:CA-BC_scale:7500000|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Area codes in Canada|778]]\n[[Category:Communications in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications-related introductions in 2001]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications-related introductions in 2013]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications-related introductions in 2019]]\n", "name_user": "2607:c000:8228:a00:852c:8331:3db3:f879", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_codes_778,_236,_and_672"}
{"title_page": "Juxtaposed controls", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{about|an arrangement between Belgium, France, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom for operating border controls on cross-Channel routes|similar arrangements in other countries|#Juxtaposed controls at other borders}}\n[[File:Bruxelles-Midi-Eurostar-Check-in-and-Passport-Control03.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Juxtaposed immigration controls at [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussel-Zuid/Bruxelles-Midi]] railway station, with the [[Belgian Federal Police]] carrying out exit immigration checks from the [[Schengen Area]] in front, and the [[UK Border Force]] carrying UK entry immigration checks behind.]]\n'''Juxtaposed controls''' (in {{lang-fr|link=no|bureaux \u00e0 contr\u00f4les nationaux juxtapos\u00e9s}}, or {{lang|fr|\"BCNJ\"}}; in {{lang-nl|link=no|kantoren waar de nationale controles van beide landen naast elkaar geschieden}}) are a reciprocal arrangement between [[Belgium]], [[France]], the [[Netherlands]] and the [[United Kingdom]] whereby [[border control]]s on certain cross-[[English Channel|Channel]] routes take place before boarding the train or ferry, rather than upon arrival after disembarkation. With the exception of the [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] route, customs checks remain unaffected by juxtaposed immigration controls and continue to take place upon arrival after disembarkation.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\">{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546809/An-Inspection-of-Juxtaposed-Controls_Aug_2013.pdf |title=An Inspection of Juxtaposed Controls (November 2012 - March 2013) |publisher=[[Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration]] |date=8 August 2013 |access-date=28 March 2020 |at=para 4.2}}</ref> Belgium, France and the Netherlands are all member states of the [[European Union]] and part of the border-free [[Schengen Area]]. The United Kingdom, on the other hand, has never participated in the Schengen Area, including when it was a member state of the European Union. As a result, juxtaposed controls aim to increase the convenience and efficiency of border checks when travelling by train or ferry between the Schengen Area and the UK by removing the need for immigration checks on arrival and by streamlining checks on departure. At the same time, juxtaposed controls are intended to detect and prevent illegal immigration. In 2016, there were over 56,000 instances when people were refused entry to the UK at the juxtaposed controls.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://homeofficemedia.blog.gov.uk/2017/07/11/fact-sheet-the-uks-juxtaposed-border-controls/ |title=Fact sheet: The UK\u2019s juxtaposed border controls |date=11 July 2017 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=[[Home Office]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rail==\n\n===Eurotunnel Shuttle===\n[[File:Eurotunnel Coquelles UK Border.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[UK Border Force]] checkpoint at the [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]], where entry checks are carried out before boarding the train to the UK.]]\nIn 1991, the Sangatte Protocol was signed between France and the UK, an agreement that provided for [[List of border crossing points in France|border]] checkpoints to be set up by France at the [[Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal]] in [[Cheriton, Kent|Cheriton]], Kent and for [[border checkpoint]]s to be set up by the UK at the [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]] in [[Coquelles]], France. The Sangatte Protocol is more formally known as the ''Protocol between the government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the government of the French Republic concerning frontier controls and policing, co-operation in criminal justice, public safety and mutual assistance relating to the Channel fixed link''.<ref name=\"gov-uk-sangatte\">{{cite web|title=Protocol between the UK and France concerning frontier controls and policing|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/protocol-between-the-uk-and-france-concerning-frontier-controls-and-policing|website=Gov.uk|publisher=Foreign & Commonwealth Office|accessdate=5 July 2016|date=5 November 1993}}</ref> The Sangatte Protocol was brought into effect in France by Decree No. 93-1136 of 24 September 1993<ref>{{cite French decree|number or usual name=n<sup>o</sup>93-1136 |date in French=24 septembre 1993 |full name=portant publication du protocole entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif aux contr\u00f4les frontaliers et \u00e0 la police, \u00e0 la coop\u00e9ration judiciaire en mati\u00e8re p\u00e9nale, \u00e0 la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 civile et \u00e0 l'assistance mutuelle, concernant la liaison fixe transmanche, sign\u00e9 \u00e0 Sangatte le 25 novembre 1991 |language=French |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000703603&dateTexte=}}</ref> and in the UK by the [[Channel Tunnel Act 1987|Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) Order 1993]].<ref name=\"1993 order\">{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=1993 | number=1813 |si=The Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) Order 1993}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the Sangatte Protocol, starting from 1994, when travelling from the UK to France by [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] (road vehicle trains), French immigration and customs checks both take place before departing from the [[Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal]], rather than on arrival in France. [[French Border Police]] and [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|Customs]] officers have the power to carry firearms and to arrest and detain individuals in the control zone.<ref name=\"1993 order\"/> The [[UK Border Force]] does not carry out routine exit checks. Instead, Eurotunnel collects passengers' travel document information during the booking or check-in process, which it sends electronically to the UK Border Force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://help.eurotunnel.com/hc/en-gb/articles/209266005-What-is-Advance-Passenger-Information-API- |title=What is Advance Passenger Information (API)? |publisher=[[Eurotunnel]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112021317/http://help.eurotunnel.com/hc/en-gb/articles/209266005-What-is-Advance-Passenger-Information-API- |archive-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Exit Checks\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exit-checks-on-passengers-leaving-the-uk/exit-checks-fact-sheet#how-exit-checks-will-work |title=Exit checks fact sheet |date=29 March 2015 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> When travelling from France to the UK by Eurotunnel Shuttle, travellers have to clear both French exit checks and UK entry immigration and customs checks at the [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]] before boarding the train. UK Border Force officers have the power to arrest and detain individuals in the control zone.<ref name=\"1993 order\"/>\n\n[[PARAFE]] self-service gates are available which eligible passengers (EU, EEA, Andorran, Monegasque, San Marinese and Swiss citizens holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use instead of a staffed counter to clear French entry immigration checks at the Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal and French exit immigration checks at the Eurotunnel Calais Terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.interieur.gouv.fr/content/download/116367/933117/file/BOMI-2019-N-5.pdf |title=D\u00e9cision du 17 avril 2019 portant autorisation de mise en service de sas utilisant le traitement de donn\u00e9es \u00e0 caract\u00e8re personnel d\u00e9nomm\u00e9 \u00abPARAFE\u00bb|publisher=[[Minister of the Interior (France)]] |date=17 April 2019 |access-date=28 March 2020 |language=French}}</ref><ref name=PARAFE>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interieur.gouv.fr/Actualites/L-actu-du-Ministere/Nos-conseils-pour-passer-l-ete-en-toute-serenite/Passez-les-controles-aux-frontieres-plus-rapidement-avec-PARAFE |title=Passez les contr\u00f4les aux fronti\u00e8res plus rapidement avec PARAFE !|language=fr-FR |publisher=[[Minister of the Interior (France)]] |date=16 July 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnlike the juxtaposed controls for the [[Eurostar]] and ferry which only consist of immigration pre-embarkation checks, juxtaposed controls for the Eurotunnel Shuttle consist of both immigration and customs pre-embarkation checks.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\"/><ref name=\"1993 order\"/>\n\nIn 2002\u20132003, at the UK immigration checkpoint at the Eurotunnel Calais Terminal in France, 2,232 people were refused entry into the UK.<ref name=\"2002/2003 stats\"/>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Prisons]], [[Peter Clarke (police officer)|Peter Clarke]], carried out an unannounced inspection of the UK's two short-term holding facilities (STHF) at the Eurotunnel Calais Terminal in France, both of which are managed by private contractor [[Mitie]]. The Chief Inspector observed 'weak safeguarding practices for children' and had 'serious concerns about adult safeguarding practice' by the UK Border Force. The Chief Inspector also raised concerns about the routine practice of detaining people in escort vehicles while awaiting the arrival of the French Border Police. He noted that few of the detainees were interviewed (regardless of their age) and their bio-data were rarely taken. Detainees refused entry to the UK would be transferred to the French Border Police, who would then release them outside the terminal area.<ref name=\"Prisons Inspector 2019 Report\">{{cite web|title=Report on unannounced inspections of the UK short-term holding facilities at France-UK Borders |url=https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmiprisons/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2020/03/France-web-2019.pdf |publisher=[[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Prisons]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ITV 2020\">{{cite news |date=13 March 2020 |title=Inspectors voice \u2018serious concerns\u2019 over UK-run immigration detention facilities |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-13/inspectors-voice-serious-concerns-over-uk-run-immigration-detention-facilities/ |work=[[ITV News]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Eurostar===\n[[File:London-St Pancras-French-immigration-control.JPG|thumb|right|300px|[[French Border Police]] checkpoint at [[London St Pancras International]] station, where entry immigration checks to the [[Schengen Area]] are carried out before boarding the train.]]\nOn 15 December 1993, a tripartite agreement was signed by Belgium, France and the UK. This agreement allowed Belgian officials to carry out pre-embarkation immigration controls at [[Waterloo International railway station|London Waterloo International]] station and British officials to carry out pre-embarkation immigration controls at [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]] station for passengers travelling on direct [[Eurostar]] train services between London and Brussels.<ref name=\"2004memorandum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2004/2589/pdfs/uksiem_20042589_en.pdf |title=Explanatory Memorandum to the Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) (Amendment) Order 2004 No. 2589 |publisher=[[Home Office]]}}</ref> The tripartite agreement was subsequently brought into effect in the UK by the Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) Order 1994,<ref>{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=1994 |number=1405 | si=The Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) Order 1994}}</ref> in France by Law No. 94-403 of 20 May 1994<ref>{{cite French law|number or usual name=n\u00b0 94-403|date in French=20 mai 1994 |language=French |full name=autorisant l'approbation de l'accord entre le Gouvernement du Royaume de Belgique, le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord concernant la circulation des trains entre la Belgique et le Royaume-Uni empruntant la liaison fixe transmanche (ensemble un protocole) |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000184017&categorieLien=id}}</ref> and Decree No. 98-172 of 10 March 1998,<ref>{{cite French decree|number or usual name=n<sup>o</sup>98-172 |date in French=10 mars 1998 |full name=portant publication de l'accord entre le Gouvernement du Royaume de Belgique, le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord concernant la circulation des trains entre la Belgique et le Royaume-Uni empruntant la liaison fixe transmanche (ensemble un protocole), sign\u00e9 \u00e0 Bruxelles le 15 d\u00e9cembre 1993 |language=French |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000204876&categorieLien=id}}</ref> and in Belgium by the Law of 29 August 1997.<ref>[http://www.ejustice.just.fgov.be/mopdf/1999/03/19_1.pdf#Page25 Loi portant approbation des actes internationaux]</ref>\n\nHowever, the pre-embarkation immigration controls arrangement did not initially apply to Eurostar trains operating between the UK and France. Initially, [[French Border Police]] officers checked passengers' travel documents while on board the train before arriving in or after departing from their station in France. No customs checks were carried out on board the train. Starting from June 1998, the French Border Police set up control booths at [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]], [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]] and [[Gare de Calais-Fr\u00e9thun|Calais-Fr\u00e9thun]] stations. This led to a gradual phasing out of onboard immigration checks (in 1998, 3,638 onboard checks were carried out, whereas in 2000, only 642 onboard checks were carried out). At Calais-Fr\u00e9thun station, passengers were routinely checked both on arrival and on departure. However, at Paris Gare du Nord and Lille Europe stations, passengers were only checked on departure and not on arrival.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senat.fr/rap/l00-240/l00-240_mono.html |title=Projet de loi relatif au contr\u00f4le des personnes empruntant la liaison ferroviaire entre la France et le Royaume-Uni |language=fr |publisher=[[Senate (France)]]}}</ref> Due to the design of the arrival train platforms at Lille Europe station, the French Border Police could only stop and check around 11% of the alighting passengers arriving from London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/11/rapports/r2985.asp |title=Rapport sur le projet de loi, adopte par le S\u00e9nat, autorisant l'approbation du Protocole additionnel au Protocole de Sangatte entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la cr\u00e9ation de bureaux charg\u00e9s du contr\u00f4le des personnes empruntant la liaison ferroviaire reliant la France et le Royaume-Uni |language=fr |publisher=[[National Assembly (France)]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2000, the 'Additional Protocol to the Sangatte Protocol' was signed between France and the UK, an agreement that provided for immigration checkpoints to be set up by France in Eurostar stations in the UK and for immigration checkpoints to be set up by the UK in Eurostar stations in France. The UK was eager to conclude the agreement with France because, for several years, many Eurostar passengers arrived in the UK without adequate documentation and a significant number claimed [[Right of asylum|asylum]] on arrival. As an illustration, in the second half of 2000, around 4,000 passengers arrived at [[Waterloo International railway station|London Waterloo]] without the correct documentation. Furthermore, under French law, there was no liability for [[SNCF]], the French railway company, to check the [[travel document]]s of Eurostar passengers (in fact, it was illegal under French law for SNCF to carry out documentation checks), which meant that the Eurostar was an easier way for [[Illegal immigration|illegal immigrants]] to travel from France to the UK than other means of transport (for example, in contrast, an airline carrier would be fined a \u00a32,000 penalty for every passenger without adequate documentation who is brought to the UK, which encouraged airlines to check the travel documents of passengers more carefully).<ref>{{cite web  |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200001/ldhansrd/vo010316/text/10316-05.htm |title=Lords Hansard text for 16 March 2001 (Column 1124-1125) |publisher=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), [[House of Lords]]}}</ref> The Additional Protocol was subsequently brought into effect in France by Law No. 2001-409 of 11 May 2001<ref>{{cite French law|number or usual name=n\u00b0 2001-409|date in French=11 mai 2001 |language=French |full name=autorisant l'approbation du protocole additionnel au protocole de Sangatte entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la cr\u00e9ation de bureaux charg\u00e9s du contr\u00f4le des personnes empruntant la liaison ferroviaire reliant la France et le Royaume-Uni |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000223217&categorieLien=id}}</ref> and in the UK by the Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) (Amendment No. 3) Order 2001.<ref>{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=2001 |number=1544 | si=The Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) (Amendment No. 3) Order 2001}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 October 2004, an Administrative Arrangement was signed by Belgium, France and the UK to extend juxtaposed controls to Eurostar services between London and Brussels which make a stop in Lille.<ref name=\"2004memorandum\"/> This was subsequently brought into effect in the UK by the Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) (Amendment) Order 2004.<ref>{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=2004 |number=2589 | si=The Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) (Amendment) Order 2004}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the agreements, when travelling from the UK to Belgium or France by Eurostar, immigration entry checks into the [[Schengen Area]] take place before boarding the train in the UK, rather than on arrival in Belgium or France. The Schengen immigration entry checks are carried out in the UK stations before embarkation by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] (which also carries out immigration entry checks on behalf of the [[Belgian Federal Police]] for passengers travelling to Belgium). [[PARAFE]] self-service gates are available at [[St Pancras railway station|London St Pancras International]] station which eligible passengers (EU, EEA, Andorran, Monegasque, San Marinese and Swiss citizens holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use to clear French immigration checks (instead of using a staffed counter).<ref name=PARAFE/> [[UK Border Force]] officers do not carry out routine exit checks. Instead, starting from April 2015, Eurostar security staff scan passengers' travel documents when entering the departure area of the station and send the information (the passenger\u2019s full name, nationality, date of birth, gender and travel document number, type and country of issue) electronically to the UK Border Force.<ref name=\"Exit Checks\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurostar4agents.com/passports-and-id |title=Passports and identity cards |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411013953/https://eurostar4agents.com/passports-and-id |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen travelling from Belgium or France to the UK by Eurostar (except on the lines from Marseille and Marne la Vall\u00e9e-Chessy, see below), passengers clear immigration exit checks from the Schengen Area, as well as UK immigration entry checks conducted by the [[UK Border Force]], before boarding the train. When departing from [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]], eligible passengers (EU, EEA, Andorran, Monegasque, San Marinese and Swiss citizens holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use [[PARAFE]] self-service gates to clear immigration exit checks from the Schengen Area (instead of using a staffed counter).<ref name=PARAFE/> [[ePassport gates]] have been installed by the UK Border Force at both [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]] and [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]], which eligible passengers (UK, EU, EEA, Swiss, Australian, Canadian, Japanese, New Zealand, Singaporean, South Korean and United States citizens (as well as other foreign nationals who have enrolled in the Registered Traveller scheme) aged 12 or over holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use to clear UK entry immigration instead of using a staffed counter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/epassport-gates-eligibility-expansion-confirmed-for-june |title=ePassport gates eligibility expansion confirmed for June |date=14 March 2019 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCustoms checks on Eurostar passengers remain unaffected by the agreements, and continue to take place upon arrival after leaving the train.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\"/><ref>Additional Protocol to the Sangatte Protocol, Article 3</ref>\n\nBetween 2002 and 2003, 2,442 passengers were refused entry into the UK at the UK immigration checkpoints in [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]] and [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]] stations on the basis that they had inadequate documentation. At [[Gare de Calais-Fr\u00e9thun|Calais-Fr\u00e9thun]] station, 56 passengers were refused entry into the UK at the UK immigration checkpoint there.<ref name=\"2002/2003 stats\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldhansrd/vo030707/text/30707w03.htm|title=Lords Hansard text for 7 Jul 2003 (230707w03) |publisher=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Lords, Westminster}}</ref>\n\nNorthbound passengers on the Marseille line disembark with their luggage at [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]] station, go through immigration and security checks and re-board the train, as [[Gare de Marseille Saint-Charles|Marseille Saint-Charles]], [[Gare d'Avignon TGV|Avignon TGV]] and [[Gare de Lyon-Part-Dieu|Lyon Part-Dieu]] do not have the space or resources to set up juxtaposed control booths there (although the previous service from [[Gare d'Avignon-Centre|Avignon Centre]] did have them). For this reason, the scheduled time of the northbound journey is around 1 hour longer than the southbound journey. This arrangement is informally known as the 'Lille shuffle'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seat61.com/news.htm |title=News |publisher=[[Seat61]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903091158/https://www.seat61.com/news.htm |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seat61.com/eurostar-to-lyon-avignon-marseille.htm |title=Direct Eurostar from London to Lyon, Avignon, Marseille |publisher=[[Seat61]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190702104937/https://www.seat61.com/eurostar-to-lyon-avignon-marseille.htm |archive-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nNorthbound passengers travelling from [[Gare de Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e\u2013Chessy|Marne la Vall\u00e9e-Chessy]] station to the UK clear French exit checks before boarding the train, and then UK entry checks at the UK arrival stations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://help.eurostar.com/faq/us-en/question/Will-our-passports-be-checked-at-Marne-la-Vall%C3%A9e-station-Disneyland-Paris |title=Will our passports be checked at Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e station (Disneyland\u00ae Paris)? |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411024226/https://help.eurostar.com/faq/us-en/question/Will-our-passports-be-checked-at-Marne-la-Vall%C3%A9e-station-Disneyland-Paris |archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/438638/response/1076214/attach/3/FOI%2046007%20response.pdf?cookie_passthrough=1 |title=Freedom of Information Response (Border control for Eurostar from Marne la Vall\u00e9e Chessy) |publisher=[[UK Border Force]] |date=27 November 2017 |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411024448/https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/438638/response/1076214/attach/3/FOI%2046007%20response.pdf?cookie_passthrough=1 |archive-date=11 April 2020 |quote=Border Force does not operate a juxtaposed control arrangement at Marne-la-Vallee Chessy station. Full UK immigration checks are conducted on arrival in the UK.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120717/text/120717w0002.htm#120717w0002.htm_wqn60 |title=House of Commons Hansard for 17 July 2012, Column 658W (Immigration Controls: St Pancras Station) |publisher=[[House of Commons]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2020, the UK [[Secretary of State for Transport|Transport Secretary]], [[Grant Shapps]], announced that passengers travelling on Eurostar from Amsterdam and Rotterdam to London would no longer have to disembark at [[Brussels-South station]], go through immigration checks and re-board the train before continuing their journey to London. Instead, starting from 30 April 2020, passengers will go through juxtaposed controls in [[Amsterdam Centraal station]] before boarding the train. Starting from 18 May 2020, passengers will go through juxtaposed controls in [[Rotterdam Centraal station]] before boarding the train.<ref name=\"Amsterdam2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transport-secretary-hails-new-horizons-for-rail-travel-across-europe |title=Transport Secretary hails new horizons for rail travel across Europe |date=4 February 2020 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"EurostarNL2020\">{{cite web |url=https://mediacentre.eurostar.com/mc_view?language=uk-en&article_Id=ka33z0000008fVpAAI |title=Eurostar transforms link between London and Amsterdam with services now direct both to and from the Netherlands |date=4 February 2020 |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328084201/https://mediacentre.eurostar.com/mc_view?language=uk-en&article_Id=ka33z0000008fVpAAI |archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Lille loophole====\nBelgium and France are both member states of the [[European Union]] and the border-free [[Schengen Area]]. The United Kingdom was until 31 January 2020 a member state of the European Union, but did not participate in the Schengen Area. Some Eurostar services from Brussels to London made a stop in Lille/Calais. On such trains, passengers who boarded in Brussels and disembarked in Lille would be travelling within the Schengen Area, and therefore not be subject to border checks. The [[Belgian Federal Police]] did not permit [[UK Border Agency]] officers stationed at the juxtaposed controls at [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]] station to question or check the documents of passengers travelling on a ticket from Brussels to Lille or Calais.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cox |first=Simon |date=8 December 2011 |title=UK border staff in arrest threat over 'Lille loophole' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-16058860 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the other hand, passengers boarding the same train in Brussels travelling on a ticket to the UK would be subject to exit checks leaving the Schengen Area and entry checks to the UK at the juxtaposed controls in Brussels-South station. This situation created a loophole (which was commonly referred to as the 'Lille loophole') whereby certain passengers who buy a train ticket from Brussels to Lille or Calais and therefore not go through the juxtaposed controls before boarding the train in Brussels, but would remain on the train after Lille/Calais and continue to the UK, thereby leaving the Schengen Area and entering the UK without having undergone the proper border checks. A number of passengers were able to travel to the UK and claim asylum on arrival in the UK using this method.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546809/An-Inspection-of-Juxtaposed-Controls_Aug_2013.pdf |title=An Inspection of Juxtaposed Controls (November 2012 - March 2013) |publisher=[[Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration]] |date=8 August 2013 |access-date=28 March 2020 |at=paras 4.3-4.4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=8 December 2011 |title=Tighter checks pledged to close Eurostar 'loophole' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-16092647 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter this loophole came to light in December 2011, Eurostar initially suspended the sale of point to point Brussels to Lille/Calais tickets, while maintaining the sale of season tickets on this route. Subsequently, Eurostar resumed the sale of tickets, but restricted the sale of Brussels-Lille/Calais tickets to 3 daily services. Upon arrival at Lille, the number of Brussels-Lille tickets sold were reconciled with the total number of disembarkations. Security guards conducted ticket inspections on passengers before the trains arrived at Calais, where those without a valid ticket to the UK would be instructed to disembark. In addition to the pre-embarkation juxtaposed controls, the UK Border Force also checked the travel documents of passengers travelling on these 3 services on arrival at London St Pancras International station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmhaff/71/71.pdf |title=The work of the UK Border Agency (December 2011\u2013March 2012) |publisher=[[House of Commons]] [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] |at=Ev 61 |date=16 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Lords/2012-04-23/debates/1204237000932/ImmigrationEurostar |title=House of Lords Hansard for 23 April 2012, Volume 736 (Immigration: Eurostar) |publisher=[[House of Lords]]}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Belgium and the UK signed an agreement clarifying that at the juxtaposed controls in Brussels-South station, 'Immigration controls performed by the United Kingdom are only permitted on passengers whose travel destination is stated to be within the United Kingdom'. Further, 'Where a person who on Belgium territory boarded an international train using the Fixed Link and has arrived in the United Kingdom is refused entry, having been found to have avoided United Kingdom immigration controls on Belgian territory by stating that their final destination is intra-Schengen, the authorities of Belgium may not refuse to accept such a person for readmittance'. The agreement entered into force on 1 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/558195/TS_32_2016_CM_9339_Channel_WEB.pdf |title=Agreement between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Nothern Ireland and the Government of the Kingdom of Belgium, concerning Immigration Controls on Rail Traffic between Belgium and the United Kingdom using the Channel Fixed Link |publisher=HM Government |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn order to close this loophole, passengers travelling from Brussels to Lille or Calais go through a different departure area in [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]] station (bypassing the juxtaposed controls for passengers heading to the UK) and travel in a separate designated coach (available in standard class only) controlled by security guards, who ensure that all of these passengers disembark at Lille/Calais before the train goes on to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurostar.com/uk-en/conditions-carriage |title=Conditions of Carriage |date=4 February 2019 |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327221758/https://www.eurostar.com/uk-en/conditions-carriage |archive-date=27 March 2020 |quote=For security and border control reasons, any booking for intra-Schengen travel from Brussels to Lille or Calais is available in Standard class only and limited to coach 18 or 16 (the \u201cDedicated Coach\u201d), depending on the type of train. Intra-Schengen passengers departing from Brussels are not subject to border controls, whether for exiting Schengen area or entering the United Kingdom. Therefore, any movement by any intra-Schengen passenger to and from the Dedicated Coach between Brussels and Lille or Calais will be strictly limited and controlled. You must cooperate with our on-board staff and agents, as well as security and border control authorities in the stations in relation to these requirements. Any failure to cooperate, any non-authorised movement to and from the Dedicated Coach and/or any refusal from any intra-Schengen passenger to get off the train at Lille or Calais may result in the intervention of security and border authorities}}</ref> Until 30 January 2017, regular commuters holding a season ticket were exempt from this measure due to the high number of travellers on peak-hour services.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pyman |first=Tom |date=23 January 2017 |title=Charlie Elphicke calls on home secretary Amber Rudd to end \u2018Lille Loophole\u2019 which allows unchecked arrivals in Kent from Europe |url=https://www.gravesendreporter.co.uk/news/charlie-elphicke-calls-on-home-secretary-amber-rudd-to-end-lille-loophole-which-allows-unchecked-arrivals-in-kent-from-europe-1-4859787 |work=Gravesend Reporter |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328140556/https://www.gravesendreporter.co.uk/news/charlie-elphicke-calls-on-home-secretary-amber-rudd-to-end-lille-loophole-which-allows-unchecked-arrivals-in-kent-from-europe-1-4859787 |archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> After this exemption was removed, regular commuters complained that only one coach (with 48 seats and standing capacity for 20 people) was allocated for passengers from Brussels to Lille on the peak hour train service departing from Brussels at 17:56.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tymen |first=Elodie |date=27 January 2017 |title=Eurostar : Londres impose des quotas pour les voyageurs entre Bruxelles et Lille |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/societes/2017/01/27/20005-20170127ARTFIG00166-eurostar-londres-impose-des-quotas-pour-les-voyageurs-non-britanniques.php |work=[[Le Figaro]] |language=French |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Aballain |first=Olivier |date=26 January 2017 |title=UE : Comment les Anglais d\u00e9cident du sort d\u2019un train Bruxelles-Lille |url=https://www.20minutes.fr/lille/2003551-20170126-ue-comment-anglais-decident-sort-train-bruxelles-lille |work=[[20 minutes (France)]] |language=French |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===List of railway stations with juxtaposed controls===\n;In Belgium<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/cellar/8ec06bfe-f76c-479b-a230-7dcd9af53966.0006.02/DOC_1|title=Update of the list of border crossing points referred to in Article 2(8) of Regulation (EC) No 562/2006 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 15 March 2006 establishing a Community Code on the rules governing the movement of persons across borders (Schengen Borders Code) (2007/C 316/01) |date=28 December 2007 |publisher=European Council }}</ref>\n* [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussel-Zuid/Bruxelles-Midi]]\n;In France<ref name=\"FRbordercrossingpoints\">{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=uriserv:OJ.C_.2020.064.01.0017.01.ENG&toc=OJ:C:2020:064:FULL |title=Update of the list of border crossing points as referred to in Article 2(8) of Regulation (EU) 2016/399 of the European Parliament and of the Council on a Union Code on the rules governing the movement of persons across borders (Schengen Borders Code) (2020/C 64/06) |date=27 February 2020 |publisher=European Council}}</ref>\n* [[Gare de Bourg-Saint-Maurice|Bourg-Saint-Maurice]]\n* [[Gare de Calais-Fr\u00e9thun|Calais\u2013Fr\u00e9thun]]\n* [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]] in [[Coquelles]]\n* [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]]\n* [[Gare de Mo\u00fbtiers-Salins-Brides-les-Bains|Mo\u00fbtiers\u2013Salins\u2013Brides-les-Bains]]\n* [[Gare du Nord|Paris Nord]]\n;In the Netherlands \n* [[Amsterdam Centraal]] (starting from 30 April 2020)<ref name=\"Amsterdam2020\"/><ref name=\"EurostarNL2020\"/>\n* [[Rotterdam Centraal]] (starting from 18 May 2020)<ref name=\"EurostarNL2020\"/>\n;In the UK<ref name=\"FRbordercrossingpoints\"/>\n* [[Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal]] in [[Cheriton, Kent]]\n* [[Ashford International railway station|Ashford International]]\n* [[Ebbsfleet International railway station|Ebbsfleet International]]\n* [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras International]]\n\n==Ferry==\n[[File:UK border control in the ferry area of the Port of Dunkerque-3749.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[UK Border Force]] checkpoint in the Port of Dunkirk, where immigration checks are carried out before boarding the ferry to Dover.]]\nOn 4 February 2003, France and the UK concluded the '''Treaty of Le Touquet''' (formally known as the ''Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom and the Government of the French Republic concerning the implementation of frontier controls at sea ports of both countries on the Channel and North Sea'').<ref name=\"ukto\">{{cite web|title=Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the French Republic concerning the Implementation of Frontier Controls at the Sea Ports of both countries on the Channel and North Sea|url=http://treaties.fco.gov.uk/treaties/treatyrecord.htm?tid=8012|website=UK Treaties Online|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"french-law\">{{cite web|title=Approbation du trait\u00e9 entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la mise en oeuvre de contr\u00f4les frontaliers dans les ports maritimes de la Manche et de la mer du Nord|url=http://www.senat.fr/leg/pjl02-433.html|website=S\u00e9nat|accessdate=5 July 2016|language=French}}</ref><ref name=\"channel4-copy-law\">{{cite web|title=Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom and the Government of the French Republic concerning the implementation of frontier controls at sea ports of both countries on the Channel and North Sea|url=http://blogs.channel4.com/factcheck/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2016/02/LeTouquetTreaty2003.pdf|website=Channel 4|accessdate=5 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420152543/http://blogs.channel4.com/factcheck/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2016/02/LeTouquetTreaty2003.pdf|archive-date=20 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> This agreement provided for juxtaposed controls on a number of cross-Channel ferry routes. The Treaty was subsequently put into effect in France by Law No. 2003-1368 of 31 December 2003<ref>{{cite French law|number or usual name=n\u00b0 2003-1368 |date in French=31 d\u00e9cembre 2003 |full name=autorisant l'approbation du trait\u00e9 entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la mise en oeuvre de contr\u00f4les frontaliers dans les ports maritimes de la Manche et de la mer du Nord des deux pays |language=French |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000609921}}</ref> and in the UK by the [[Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002 (Juxtaposed Controls) Order 2003]], under the authority of the [[Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002]].<ref name=\"2003 order\">{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=2003 |number=2818 |si=The Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002 (Juxtaposed Controls) Order 2003}}</ref>\n\nFrance has established immigration checkpoints at the [[Port of Dover]], where the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] carries out immigration entry checks into the [[Schengen Area]] on passengers travelling to [[Calais]] or [[Dunkirk]]. French Border Police officers have the power to carry firearms and to arrest and detain individuals in the immigration control zone in the Port of Dover.<ref name=\"2003 order\"/> On the other hand, the [[UK Border Force]] does not carry out routine exit checks at the Port of Dover. Instead, since April 2015, the ferry operator collects passengers' travel document information during the booking or check-in process, which it sends electronically to the UK Border Force. However, coaches carrying organised school groups (consisting of students aged 16 and under accompanied by teachers or other responsible adults) are exempt from having their travel document information collected and sent to the UK Border Force.<ref name=\"Exit Checks\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doverport.co.uk/about/news/introduction-of-government-imposed-exit-checks-at/12953/ |title=Introduction of Government-imposed Exit Checks at Port of Dover |publisher=[[Port of Dover]] |date=12 March 2015 |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411041133/https://www.doverport.co.uk/about/news/introduction-of-government-imposed-exit-checks-at/12953/ |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt present, the UK has immigration checkpoints at the ports of [[Port of Calais|Calais]] and Dunkirk (previously, the UK also had an immigration checkpoint at the port of [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]]). UK Border Force officers have the power to arrest and detain individuals in the immigration control zone in the ports of Calais and Dunkirk.<ref name=\"2003 order\"/> Passengers travelling from Calais and Dunkirk to the UK go through French exit checks as well as UK immigration entry checks before embarkation.\n\nCustoms checks on ferry passengers remain unaffected by the Treaty and continue to take place upon arrival after leaving the ferry. Therefore, when travelling from France to [[Dover]], although ferry passengers have already gone through immigration checks before departure, when they arrive in the UK, they might still be stopped by customs officers for a customs inspection. Similarly, when travelling from Dover to France, although ferry passengers have already been through immigration checks by the French Border Police at Dover, they might still be subject to a customs check by [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|French Customs]] on arrival in France.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\"/>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2007, 10,766 people were refused entry into the UK by UK immigration officers stationed in Calais.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200708/ldselect/ldeucom/60/60we05.htm|title=Written evidence by the Home Office Border Controls at Calais and Coquelles |date=16 January 2008 |publisher=[[House of Lords]] [[European Union Committee]]}}</ref>\n\nA Joint Operational Coordination Centre has been created at the Port of Calais to strengthen co-operation between the [[UK Border Force]], [[French Border Police]] and [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|French Customs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/257276/declaration.pdf |title=UK-France Summit, 2 November 2010 \u2013 Declaration on Immigration |publisher=HM Government}}</ref>\n\nSince 2011, private security officers employed by Eamus Cork Solutions (ECS) work in the freight lanes at the juxtaposed controls at the Port of Calais and the Port of Dunkirk. Their job is to detect people concealed inside vehicles attempting to enter the UK through visual inspections, sniffer dogs, or by equipment including heartbeat monitors, carbon dioxide detectors and scanners.<ref name=\"Bosworth\">{{cite journal |last=Bosworth |first=Mary |date= |title=Immigration detention and juxtaposed border controls on the French north coast |url=https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:7058db27-e9dc-4385-b35e-8e10ae96cfa1/download_file?file_format=pdf&safe_filename=calais_revised_31.10.19.pdf&type_of_work=Journal+article |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411140650/https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:7058db27-e9dc-4385-b35e-8e10ae96cfa1/download_file?file_format=pdf&safe_filename=calais_revised_31.10.19.pdf&type_of_work=Journal+article |journal=European Journal of Criminology |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=19 September 2016 |title=Home Office prepared to pay up to \u00a380m for French port security |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-37411314 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the UK-France Summit held at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] on 18 January 2018, [[President of France|French President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|UK Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] announced that the UK would provide an additional \u20ac50 million in financial support for 2018 for France to strengthen border security (including fencing, CCTV and detection technology) at the juxtaposed controls at the Port of Calais, as well as to establish accommodation facilities located outside the Calais and Dunkirk areas, such as Reception and Assessment Centres.<ref>{{cite web|title=United Kingdom-France Summit Communique |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/674880/2018_UK-FR_Summit_Communique.pdf |date=18 January 2018 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The two countries also agreed to a treaty (known as the '''Sandhurst Treaty''')<ref name=\"HL Paper 428\"/> with provisions to implement the [[Dublin III Regulation]] concerning the treatment of unaccompanied asylum seeking children and to establish a Joint Information and Coordination Centre (in French: Centre Conjoint d\u2019Information et de Coordination, or CCIC). The Sandhurst Treaty entered into force on 1 February 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the French Republic Concerning the Reinforcement of Cooperation for the Coordinated Management of their Shared Border |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/678596/TS01.2018_Cm9568_UK_France_Shared_Border_WEB.pdf |date=18 January 2018 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> and the Joint Centre became operational on 23 November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joint UK-France centre opens in Calais to tackle criminality at border |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/joint-uk-france-centre-opens-in-calais-to-tackle-criminality-at-border |date=27 November 2018 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Minister of the Interior (France)|French Minister of the Interior]], [[Christophe Castaner]], has stated that if the juxtaposed controls were removed, it would lead to increased waiting times for travellers to clear immigration and customs on arrival.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doubles contr\u00f4les douaniers \u00e0 Calais |url=https://www.senat.fr/questions/base/2019/qSEQ190309586.html |date=18 April 2019 |publisher=[[Senate (France)]] |language=fr |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Prisons]], [[Peter Clarke (police officer)|Peter Clarke]], carried out an unannounced inspection of the UK's short-term holding facility (STHF) at the Port of Calais, which is managed by private contractor [[Mitie]]. The Chief Inspector raised concerns about the routine practice of detaining people in caged escort vehicles that were in 'appalling condition, with ripped out seats' for 'prolonged periods' while awaiting the arrival of the French Border Police. Few of the detainees were interviewed and UK Border Force officers could not state the legal authority under which these detainees were held. Detainees refused entry to the UK would be handed to the French Border Police and then be released outside the port area.<ref name=\"Prisons Inspector 2019 Report\"/><ref name=\"ITV 2020\"/> No onsite medical care or access to legal advice is provided in the STHF.<ref name=\"Bosworth\"/>\n\nUK Border Force officers and Detainee Custody Officers (DCOs) employed by [[Mitie]] who work at the juxtaposed controls are either bussed in daily across the Channel from their homes in [[Kent]], or they reside four nights a week in a hotel in Calais.<ref name=\"Bosworth\"/>\n\n==Air==\nThere are no juxtaposed controls on cross-Channel air travel. Air carriers are required under UK and Schengen rules to perform checks before boarding that passengers possess travel documents to enter the destination country.<ref>{{Cite legislation UK | type = act | year = 1999 | chapter = 33 | act = Immigration and Asylum Act | section = 40}}</ref><ref>[https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=celex%3A42000A0922%2802%29 Schengen Convention], Article 26(1)(b)</ref><ref>[https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri=uriserv%3AOJ.L_.2001.187.01.0045.01.ENG Council Directive 2001/51/EC of 28 June 2001 supplementing the provisions of Article 26 of the Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement of 14 June 1985 (Carriers Liability Directive)]</ref> Passengers flying from the [[Schengen Area]] to the UK undergo Schengen exit checks at the departure airport and entry checks by the [[UK Border Force]] at the arrival airport in the UK. For passengers flying from the UK to the Schengen Area, the UK Border Force does not conduct routine exit checks. Instead, the air carrier takes passengers' travel document information during the check-in process, which is transmitted electronically to the UK Border Force.<ref name=\"Exit Checks\"/> Passengers then go through Schengen entry immigration and customs checks on arrival in the Schengen Area.\n\n==Implications of the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union==\nThe [[House of Lords]] [[European Union Committee]] has observed that the Treaty of Le Touquet led to a 'build-up of pressure in the Calais region of people who seek to come to the UK but who do not fulfil immigration requirements and are unable to seek asylum in the UK from France', and that the 'continuous establishment of unregulated camp sites for people in this position is an irritant in French politics'. As a consequence, after the result of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]], there were increased calls in France to scrap the Treaty of Le Touquet and end juxtaposed controls, including from the then French Presidential candidates [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]] and [[Emmanuel Macron]], and from the [[List of the mayors of Calais|Mayor of Calais]], [[Natacha Bouchart]]. However, such calls have since receded, as political leaders in France and the UK have sought to reinforce their commitment to bilateral border cooperation (for example, by entering into the Sandhurst Treaty). At the same time, the Committee has noted that although the agreements establishing juxtaposed controls are 'not formally EU-dependent, the agreements underpinning bilateral border cooperation have undoubtedly been easier to sustain under the shared umbrella of EU membership'.<ref name=\"HL Paper 428\">{{cite web|title=48th Report of Session 2017\u201319 - Brexit: refugee protection and asylum policy (HL Paper 428) |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201719/ldselect/ldeucom/428/42806.htm#footnote-124-backlink |date=11 October 2019 |publisher=[[House of Lords]] [[European Union Committee]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom [[Brexit|ceased to be a member state of the European Union]]. During the transition period that is set to end on 31 December 2020, the arrangements for juxtaposed controls remain unchanged.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurostar.com/rw-en/brexit |title=Eurostar and Brexit |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:France LFT Londres passport stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Entry stamp]] into the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras International]] station. ('LFT' stands for 'Liaison fixe transmanche' (literally: cross-Channel fixed link))\nFile:France BCNJ Douvres.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Entry stamp]] into the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at the [[Port of Dover]]. ('BCNJ' stands for 'Bureaux \u00e0 contr\u00f4les nationaux juxtapos\u00e9s' (literally: juxtaposed national countrol booths))\nFile:Brussels Zuid Midi Station passport stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Exit stamp]] from the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Belgian Federal Police]] at [[Brussels-South railway station]].\nFile:France LFT Lille Europe stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Exit stamp]] from the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at [[Lille Europe]] station. ('LFT' stands for 'Liaison fixe transmanche' (literally: cross-Channel fixed link))\nFile:France LFT Paris Nord passport stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Exit stamp]] from the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at [[Paris Gare du Nord]] station. ('LFT' stands for 'Liaison fixe transmanche' (literally: cross-Channel fixed link))\nFile:USA Passport Channel Tunnel and Gare du Nord.jpg|Pair of passport stamps (exit from France, entry into the UK) at the juxtaposed border controls at [[Paris Gare du Nord]] station.\nFile:UKE HENSLEY.JPG|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Force]] at [[Paris Gare du Nord]] station.\nFile:UK Frethun passport stamp.jpg|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Agency]] at [[Calais-Fr\u00e9thun]] station.\nFile:UK Calais passport stamp.jpg|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Force]] at the [[Port of Calais]].\nFile:UK Brussels passport stamp.jpg|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Agency]] at [[Brussels-South railway station]].\n</gallery>\n\n==Juxtaposed controls at other borders==\nApart from the borders along the English Channel, juxtaposed border controls or similar arrangements exist in other countries:\n*[[United States border preclearance]] (a similar arrangement whereby the US carries out pre-embarkation immigration checks at some airports and border crossing points in Canada, the Caribbean, Ireland, and the United Arab Emirates)\n*[[Shenzhen Bay Control Point]] (a similar arrangement whereby Hong Kong carries out immigration checks at the border crossing point geographically located in the [[Mainland China|Mainland]], but the area is designated as if it is part of Hong Kong and Hong Kong law fully applies)\n*[[West Kowloon railway station]] [[West Kowloon Station Mainland Port Area|control point]]<ref>[http://gia.info.gov.hk/general/201707/25/P2017072500891_264072_1_1500987862639.pdf Press Conference on the Co-location Arrangement of the Hong Kong Section of the Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link] </ref> ([[Bill (law)|bill]] introduced to the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] in early 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201801/17/P2018011700514.htm|title=LCQ4: Co-location Arrangement of Hong Kong Section of Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link|website=www.info.gov.hk}}</ref><ref>[https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr17-18/english/bc/bc102/general/bc102.htm Bills Committee on Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link (Co-location) Bill]</ref> passed on 14 June 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/2150873/hong-kongs-controversial-china-rail-checkpoint-bill-finally|title=Hong Kong\u2019s controversial China rail checkpoint bill finally passed|date=14 June 2018|website=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref>\n*[[Woodlands Train Checkpoint]] (a similar arrangement where passengers undergo Malaysian entry formalities at the station, despite it being located in Singaporean territory)\n*[[Padang Besar railway station]] in [[Padang Besar, Malaysia]] which houses CIQ facilities for both [[Malaysia]] and [[Thailand]] despite being wholly within Malaysia territory.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.malaysiatrains.com/padang-besar-railway-station-train-times-tickets/ | title=Padang Besar Railway Station \u2013 Train times & tickets| publisher=Malaysia Trains|language=English|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Princess Juliana International Airport]], [[Sint Maarten]] and [[Grand Case-Esp\u00e9rance Airport]], [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]] (where there are joint border controls pursuant to the [[Franco-Dutch treaty on Saint Martin border controls]])\n\n==See also==\n*[[Migrants around Calais]]\n*[[List of border crossing points in France]]\n*[[Belgian Federal Police]]\n*[[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res (French Border Police)]]\n*[[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes (French Customs)]]\n*[[Royal Marechaussee|Royal Marechaussee (The Netherlands)]]\n*[[UK Border Force]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Ryan, Bernard. ''Extraterritorial Immigration Control: Legal Challenges''. [[Martinus Nijhoff Publishers]], 2010, pp.&nbsp;16\u201319\n\n[[Category:International border crossings]]\n[[Category:Border crossings of France]]\n[[Category:International travel documents]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in Europe]]\n[[Category:Transport and the European Union]]\n[[Category:Calais migrant crisis (1999\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Border crossings of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Border crossings of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Juxtaposed border controls]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{about|an arrangement between Belgium, France, the Netherlands and the United Kingdom for operating border controls on cross-Channel routes|similar arrangements in other countries|#Juxtaposed controls at other borders}}\n[[File:Bruxelles-Midi-Eurostar-Check-in-and-Passport-Control03.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Juxtaposed immigration controls at [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussel-Zuid/Bruxelles-Midi]] railway station, with the [[Belgian Federal Police]] carrying out exit immigration checks from the [[Schengen Area]] in front, and the [[UK Border Force]] carrying UK entry immigration checks behind.]]\n'''Juxtaposed controls''' (in {{lang-fr|link=no|bureaux \u00e0 contr\u00f4les nationaux juxtapos\u00e9s}}, or {{lang|fr|\"BCNJ\"}}; in {{lang-nl|link=no|kantoren waar de nationale controles van beide landen naast elkaar geschieden}}) are a reciprocal arrangement between [[Belgium]], [[France]], the [[Netherlands]] and the [[United Kingdom]] whereby [[border control]]s on certain cross-[[English Channel|Channel]] routes take place before boarding the train or ferry, rather than upon arrival after disembarkation. With the exception of the [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] route, customs checks remain unaffected by juxtaposed immigration controls and continue to take place upon arrival after disembarkation.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\">{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546809/An-Inspection-of-Juxtaposed-Controls_Aug_2013.pdf |title=An Inspection of Juxtaposed Controls (November 2012 - March 2013) |publisher=[[Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration]] |date=8 August 2013 |access-date=28 March 2020 |at=para 4.2}}</ref> Belgium, France and the Netherlands are all member states of the [[European Union]] and part of the border-free [[Schengen Area]]. The United Kingdom, on the other hand, has never participated in the Schengen Area, including when it was a member state of the European Union. As a result, juxtaposed controls aim to increase the convenience and efficiency of border checks when travelling by train or ferry between the Schengen Area and the UK by removing the need for immigration checks on arrival and by streamlining checks on departure. At the same time, juxtaposed controls are intended to detect and prevent illegal immigration. In 2016, there were over 56,000 instances when people were refused entry to the UK at the juxtaposed controls.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://homeofficemedia.blog.gov.uk/2017/07/11/fact-sheet-the-uks-juxtaposed-border-controls/ |title=Fact sheet: The UK\u2019s juxtaposed border controls |date=11 July 2017 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=[[Home Office]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Rail==\n\n===Eurotunnel Shuttle===\n[[File:Eurotunnel Coquelles UK Border.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[UK Border Force]] checkpoint at the [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]], where entry checks are carried out before boarding the train to the UK.]]\nIn 1991, the Sangatte Protocol was signed between France and the UK, an agreement that provided for [[List of border crossing points in France|border]] checkpoints to be set up by France at the [[Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal]] in [[Cheriton, Kent|Cheriton]], Kent and for [[border checkpoint]]s to be set up by the UK at the [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]] in [[Coquelles]], France. The Sangatte Protocol is more formally known as the ''Protocol between the government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the government of the French Republic concerning frontier controls and policing, co-operation in criminal justice, public safety and mutual assistance relating to the Channel fixed link''.<ref name=\"gov-uk-sangatte\">{{cite web|title=Protocol between the UK and France concerning frontier controls and policing|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/protocol-between-the-uk-and-france-concerning-frontier-controls-and-policing|website=Gov.uk|publisher=Foreign & Commonwealth Office|accessdate=5 July 2016|date=5 November 1993}}</ref> The Sangatte Protocol was brought into effect in France by Decree No. 93-1136 of 24 September 1993<ref>{{cite French decree|number or usual name=n<sup>o</sup>93-1136 |date in French=24 septembre 1993 |full name=portant publication du protocole entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif aux contr\u00f4les frontaliers et \u00e0 la police, \u00e0 la coop\u00e9ration judiciaire en mati\u00e8re p\u00e9nale, \u00e0 la s\u00e9curit\u00e9 civile et \u00e0 l'assistance mutuelle, concernant la liaison fixe transmanche, sign\u00e9 \u00e0 Sangatte le 25 novembre 1991 |language=French |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000703603&dateTexte=}}</ref> and in the UK by the [[Channel Tunnel Act 1987|Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) Order 1993]].<ref name=\"1993 order\">{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=1993 | number=1813 |si=The Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) Order 1993}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the Sangatte Protocol, starting from 1994, when travelling from the UK to France by [[Eurotunnel Shuttle]] (road vehicle trains), French immigration and customs checks both take place before departing from the [[Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal]], rather than on arrival in France. [[French Border Police]] and [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|Customs]] officers have the power to carry firearms and to arrest and detain individuals in the control zone.<ref name=\"1993 order\"/> The [[UK Border Force]] does not carry out routine exit checks. Instead, Eurotunnel collects passengers' travel document information during the booking or check-in process, which it sends electronically to the UK Border Force.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://help.eurotunnel.com/hc/en-gb/articles/209266005-What-is-Advance-Passenger-Information-API- |title=What is Advance Passenger Information (API)? |publisher=[[Eurotunnel]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112021317/http://help.eurotunnel.com/hc/en-gb/articles/209266005-What-is-Advance-Passenger-Information-API- |archive-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Exit Checks\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exit-checks-on-passengers-leaving-the-uk/exit-checks-fact-sheet#how-exit-checks-will-work |title=Exit checks fact sheet |date=29 March 2015 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> When travelling from France to the UK by Eurotunnel Shuttle, travellers have to clear both French exit checks and UK entry immigration and customs checks at the [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]] before boarding the train. UK Border Force officers have the power to arrest and detain individuals in the control zone.<ref name=\"1993 order\"/>\n\n[[PARAFE]] self-service gates are available which eligible passengers (EU, EEA, Andorran, Monegasque, San Marinese and Swiss citizens holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use instead of a staffed counter to clear French entry immigration checks at the Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal and French exit immigration checks at the Eurotunnel Calais Terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.interieur.gouv.fr/content/download/116367/933117/file/BOMI-2019-N-5.pdf |title=D\u00e9cision du 17 avril 2019 portant autorisation de mise en service de sas utilisant le traitement de donn\u00e9es \u00e0 caract\u00e8re personnel d\u00e9nomm\u00e9 \u00abPARAFE\u00bb|publisher=[[Minister of the Interior (France)]] |date=17 April 2019 |access-date=28 March 2020 |language=French}}</ref><ref name=PARAFE>{{Cite web|url=https://www.interieur.gouv.fr/Actualites/L-actu-du-Ministere/Nos-conseils-pour-passer-l-ete-en-toute-serenite/Passez-les-controles-aux-frontieres-plus-rapidement-avec-PARAFE |title=Passez les contr\u00f4les aux fronti\u00e8res plus rapidement avec PARAFE !|language=fr-FR |publisher=[[Minister of the Interior (France)]] |date=16 July 2019|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnlike the juxtaposed controls for the [[Eurostar]] and ferry which only consist of immigration pre-embarkation checks, juxtaposed controls for the Eurotunnel Shuttle consist of both immigration and customs pre-embarkation checks.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\"/><ref name=\"1993 order\"/>\n\nIn 2002\u20132003, at the UK immigration checkpoint at the Eurotunnel Calais Terminal in France, 2,232 people were refused entry into the UK.<ref name=\"2002/2003 stats\"/>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Prisons]], [[Peter Clarke (police officer)|Peter Clarke]], carried out an unannounced inspection of the UK's two short-term holding facilities (STHF) at the Eurotunnel Calais Terminal in France, both of which are managed by private contractor [[Mitie]]. The Chief Inspector observed 'weak safeguarding practices for children' and had 'serious concerns about adult safeguarding practice' by the UK Border Force. The Chief Inspector also raised concerns about the routine practice of detaining people in escort vehicles while awaiting the arrival of the French Border Police. He noted that few of the detainees were interviewed (regardless of their age) and their bio-data were rarely taken. Detainees refused entry to the UK would be transferred to the French Border Police, who would then release them outside the terminal area.<ref name=\"Prisons Inspector 2019 Report\">{{cite web|title=Report on unannounced inspections of the UK short-term holding facilities at France-UK Borders |url=https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmiprisons/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2020/03/France-web-2019.pdf |publisher=[[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Prisons]] |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ITV 2020\">{{cite news |date=13 March 2020 |title=Inspectors voice \u2018serious concerns\u2019 over UK-run immigration detention facilities |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-13/inspectors-voice-serious-concerns-over-uk-run-immigration-detention-facilities/ |work=[[ITV News]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Eurostar===\n[[File:London-St Pancras-French-immigration-control.JPG|thumb|right|300px|[[French Border Police]] checkpoint at [[London St Pancras International]] station, where entry immigration checks to the [[Schengen Area]] are carried out before boarding the train.]]\nOn 15 December 1993, a tripartite agreement was signed by Belgium, France and the UK. This agreement allowed Belgian officials to carry out pre-embarkation immigration controls at [[Waterloo International railway station|London Waterloo International]] station and British officials to carry out pre-embarkation immigration controls at [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]] station for passengers travelling on direct [[Eurostar]] train services between London and Brussels.<ref name=\"2004memorandum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2004/2589/pdfs/uksiem_20042589_en.pdf |title=Explanatory Memorandum to the Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) (Amendment) Order 2004 No. 2589 |publisher=[[Home Office]]}}</ref> The tripartite agreement was subsequently brought into effect in the UK by the Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) Order 1994,<ref>{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=1994 |number=1405 | si=The Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) Order 1994}}</ref> in France by Law No. 94-403 of 20 May 1994<ref>{{cite French law|number or usual name=n\u00b0 94-403|date in French=20 mai 1994 |language=French |full name=autorisant l'approbation de l'accord entre le Gouvernement du Royaume de Belgique, le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord concernant la circulation des trains entre la Belgique et le Royaume-Uni empruntant la liaison fixe transmanche (ensemble un protocole) |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000184017&categorieLien=id}}</ref> and Decree No. 98-172 of 10 March 1998,<ref>{{cite French decree|number or usual name=n<sup>o</sup>98-172 |date in French=10 mars 1998 |full name=portant publication de l'accord entre le Gouvernement du Royaume de Belgique, le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord concernant la circulation des trains entre la Belgique et le Royaume-Uni empruntant la liaison fixe transmanche (ensemble un protocole), sign\u00e9 \u00e0 Bruxelles le 15 d\u00e9cembre 1993 |language=French |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000204876&categorieLien=id}}</ref> and in Belgium by the Law of 29 August 1997.<ref>[http://www.ejustice.just.fgov.be/mopdf/1999/03/19_1.pdf#Page25 Loi portant approbation des actes internationaux]</ref>\n\nHowever, the pre-embarkation immigration controls arrangement did not initially apply to Eurostar trains operating between the UK and France. Initially, [[French Border Police]] officers checked passengers' travel documents while on board the train before arriving in or after departing from their station in France. No customs checks were carried out on board the train. Starting from June 1998, the French Border Police set up control booths at [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]], [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]] and [[Gare de Calais-Fr\u00e9thun|Calais-Fr\u00e9thun]] stations. This led to a gradual phasing out of onboard immigration checks (in 1998, 3,638 onboard checks were carried out, whereas in 2000, only 642 onboard checks were carried out). At Calais-Fr\u00e9thun station, passengers were routinely checked both on arrival and on departure. However, at Paris Gare du Nord and Lille Europe stations, passengers were only checked on departure and not on arrival.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.senat.fr/rap/l00-240/l00-240_mono.html |title=Projet de loi relatif au contr\u00f4le des personnes empruntant la liaison ferroviaire entre la France et le Royaume-Uni |language=fr |publisher=[[Senate (France)]]}}</ref> Due to the design of the arrival train platforms at Lille Europe station, the French Border Police could only stop and check around 11% of the alighting passengers arriving from London.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/11/rapports/r2985.asp |title=Rapport sur le projet de loi, adopte par le S\u00e9nat, autorisant l'approbation du Protocole additionnel au Protocole de Sangatte entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la cr\u00e9ation de bureaux charg\u00e9s du contr\u00f4le des personnes empruntant la liaison ferroviaire reliant la France et le Royaume-Uni |language=fr |publisher=[[National Assembly (France)]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 May 2000, the 'Additional Protocol to the Sangatte Protocol' was signed between France and the UK, an agreement that provided for immigration checkpoints to be set up by France in Eurostar stations in the UK and for immigration checkpoints to be set up by the UK in Eurostar stations in France. The UK was eager to conclude the agreement with France because, for several years, many Eurostar passengers arrived in the UK without adequate documentation and a significant number claimed [[Right of asylum|asylum]] on arrival. As an illustration, in the second half of 2000, around 4,000 passengers arrived at [[Waterloo International railway station|London Waterloo]] without the correct documentation. Furthermore, under French law, there was no liability for [[SNCF]], the French railway company, to check the [[travel document]]s of Eurostar passengers (in fact, it was illegal under French law for SNCF to carry out documentation checks), which meant that the Eurostar was an easier way for [[Illegal immigration|illegal immigrants]] to travel from France to the UK than other means of transport (for example, in contrast, an airline carrier would be fined a \u00a32,000 penalty for every passenger without adequate documentation who is brought to the UK, which encouraged airlines to check the travel documents of passengers more carefully).<ref>{{cite web  |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200001/ldhansrd/vo010316/text/10316-05.htm |title=Lords Hansard text for 16 March 2001 (Column 1124-1125) |publisher=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), [[House of Lords]]}}</ref> The Additional Protocol was subsequently brought into effect in France by Law No. 2001-409 of 11 May 2001<ref>{{cite French law|number or usual name=n\u00b0 2001-409|date in French=11 mai 2001 |language=French |full name=autorisant l'approbation du protocole additionnel au protocole de Sangatte entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la cr\u00e9ation de bureaux charg\u00e9s du contr\u00f4le des personnes empruntant la liaison ferroviaire reliant la France et le Royaume-Uni |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000223217&categorieLien=id}}</ref> and in the UK by the Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) (Amendment No. 3) Order 2001.<ref>{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=2001 |number=1544 | si=The Channel Tunnel (International Arrangements) (Amendment No. 3) Order 2001}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 October 2004, an Administrative Arrangement was signed by Belgium, France and the UK to extend juxtaposed controls to Eurostar services between London and Brussels which make a stop in Lille.<ref name=\"2004memorandum\"/> This was subsequently brought into effect in the UK by the Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) (Amendment) Order 2004.<ref>{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=2004 |number=2589 | si=The Channel Tunnel (Miscellaneous Provisions) (Amendment) Order 2004}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the agreements, when travelling from the UK to Belgium or France by Eurostar, immigration entry checks into the [[Schengen Area]] take place before boarding the train in the UK, rather than on arrival in Belgium or France. The Schengen immigration entry checks are carried out in the UK stations before embarkation by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] (which also carries out immigration entry checks on behalf of the [[Belgian Federal Police]] for passengers travelling to Belgium). [[PARAFE]] self-service gates are available at [[St Pancras railway station|London St Pancras International]] station which eligible passengers (EU, EEA, Andorran, Monegasque, San Marinese and Swiss citizens holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use to clear French immigration checks (instead of using a staffed counter).<ref name=PARAFE/> [[UK Border Force]] officers do not carry out routine exit checks. Instead, starting from April 2015, Eurostar security staff scan passengers' travel documents when entering the departure area of the station and send the information (the passenger\u2019s full name, nationality, date of birth, gender and travel document number, type and country of issue) electronically to the UK Border Force.<ref name=\"Exit Checks\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurostar4agents.com/passports-and-id |title=Passports and identity cards |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200411013953/https://eurostar4agents.com/passports-and-id |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen travelling from Belgium or France to the UK by Eurostar (except on the lines from Marseille and Marne la Vall\u00e9e-Chessy, see below), passengers clear immigration exit checks from the Schengen Area, as well as UK immigration entry checks conducted by the [[UK Border Force]], before boarding the train. When departing from [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]], eligible passengers (EU, EEA, Andorran, Monegasque, San Marinese and Swiss citizens holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use [[PARAFE]] self-service gates to clear immigration exit checks from the Schengen Area (instead of using a staffed counter).<ref name=PARAFE/> [[ePassport gates]] have been installed by the UK Border Force at both [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]] and [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]], which eligible passengers (UK, EU, EEA, Swiss, Australian, Canadian, Japanese, New Zealand, Singaporean, South Korean and United States citizens (as well as other foreign nationals who have enrolled in the Registered Traveller scheme) aged 12 or over holding [[biometric passport]]s) can use to clear UK entry immigration instead of using a staffed counter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/epassport-gates-eligibility-expansion-confirmed-for-june |title=ePassport gates eligibility expansion confirmed for June |date=14 March 2019 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCustoms checks on Eurostar passengers remain unaffected by the agreements, and continue to take place upon arrival after leaving the train.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\"/><ref>Additional Protocol to the Sangatte Protocol, Article 3</ref>\n\nBetween 2002 and 2003, 2,442 passengers were refused entry into the UK at the UK immigration checkpoints in [[Gare du Nord|Paris Gare du Nord]] and [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]] stations on the basis that they had inadequate documentation. At [[Gare de Calais-Fr\u00e9thun|Calais-Fr\u00e9thun]] station, 56 passengers were refused entry into the UK at the UK immigration checkpoint there.<ref name=\"2002/2003 stats\">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200203/ldhansrd/vo030707/text/30707w03.htm|title=Lords Hansard text for 7 Jul 2003 (230707w03) |publisher=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Lords, Westminster}}</ref>\n\nNorthbound passengers on the Marseille line disembark with their luggage at [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]] station, go through immigration and security checks and re-board the train, as [[Gare de Marseille Saint-Charles|Marseille Saint-Charles]], [[Gare d'Avignon TGV|Avignon TGV]] and [[Gare de Lyon-Part-Dieu|Lyon Part-Dieu]] do not have the space or resources to set up juxtaposed control booths there (although the previous service from [[Gare d'Avignon-Centre|Avignon Centre]] did have them). For this reason, the scheduled time of the northbound journey is around 1 hour longer than the southbound journey. This arrangement is informally known as the 'Lille shuffle'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seat61.com/news.htm |title=News |publisher=[[Seat61]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903091158/https://www.seat61.com/news.htm |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seat61.com/eurostar-to-lyon-avignon-marseille.htm |title=Direct Eurostar from London to Lyon, Avignon, Marseille |publisher=[[Seat61]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20190702104937/https://www.seat61.com/eurostar-to-lyon-avignon-marseille.htm |archive-date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nNorthbound passengers travelling from [[Gare de Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e\u2013Chessy|Marne la Vall\u00e9e-Chessy]] station to the UK clear French exit checks before boarding the train, and then UK entry checks at the UK arrival stations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://help.eurostar.com/faq/us-en/question/Will-our-passports-be-checked-at-Marne-la-Vall%C3%A9e-station-Disneyland-Paris |title=Will our passports be checked at Marne-la-Vall\u00e9e station (Disneyland\u00ae Paris)? |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411024226/https://help.eurostar.com/faq/us-en/question/Will-our-passports-be-checked-at-Marne-la-Vall%C3%A9e-station-Disneyland-Paris |archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/438638/response/1076214/attach/3/FOI%2046007%20response.pdf?cookie_passthrough=1 |title=Freedom of Information Response (Border control for Eurostar from Marne la Vall\u00e9e Chessy) |publisher=[[UK Border Force]] |date=27 November 2017 |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411024448/https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/438638/response/1076214/attach/3/FOI%2046007%20response.pdf?cookie_passthrough=1 |archive-date=11 April 2020 |quote=Border Force does not operate a juxtaposed control arrangement at Marne-la-Vallee Chessy station. Full UK immigration checks are conducted on arrival in the UK.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120717/text/120717w0002.htm#120717w0002.htm_wqn60 |title=House of Commons Hansard for 17 July 2012, Column 658W (Immigration Controls: St Pancras Station) |publisher=[[House of Commons]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2020, the UK [[Secretary of State for Transport|Transport Secretary]], [[Grant Shapps]], announced that passengers travelling on Eurostar from Amsterdam and Rotterdam to London would no longer have to disembark at [[Brussels-South station]], go through immigration checks and re-board the train before continuing their journey to London. Instead, starting from 30 April 2020, passengers will go through juxtaposed controls in [[Amsterdam Centraal station]] before boarding the train. Starting from 18 May 2020, passengers will go through juxtaposed controls in [[Rotterdam Centraal station]] before boarding the train.<ref name=\"Amsterdam2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transport-secretary-hails-new-horizons-for-rail-travel-across-europe |title=Transport Secretary hails new horizons for rail travel across Europe |date=4 February 2020 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"EurostarNL2020\">{{cite web |url=https://mediacentre.eurostar.com/mc_view?language=uk-en&article_Id=ka33z0000008fVpAAI |title=Eurostar transforms link between London and Amsterdam with services now direct both to and from the Netherlands |date=4 February 2020 |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328084201/https://mediacentre.eurostar.com/mc_view?language=uk-en&article_Id=ka33z0000008fVpAAI |archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Lille loophole====\nBelgium and France are both member states of the [[European Union]] and the border-free [[Schengen Area]]. The United Kingdom was until 31 January 2020 a member state of the European Union, but did not participate in the Schengen Area. Some Eurostar services from Brussels to London made a stop in Lille/Calais. On such trains, passengers who boarded in Brussels and disembarked in Lille would be travelling within the Schengen Area, and therefore not be subject to border checks. The [[Belgian Federal Police]] did not permit [[UK Border Agency]] officers stationed at the juxtaposed controls at [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]] station to question or check the documents of passengers travelling on a ticket from Brussels to Lille or Calais.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cox |first=Simon |date=8 December 2011 |title=UK border staff in arrest threat over 'Lille loophole' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-16058860 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> On the other hand, passengers boarding the same train in Brussels travelling on a ticket to the UK would be subject to exit checks leaving the Schengen Area and entry checks to the UK at the juxtaposed controls in Brussels-South station. This situation created a loophole (which was commonly referred to as the 'Lille loophole') whereby certain passengers who buy a train ticket from Brussels to Lille or Calais and therefore not go through the juxtaposed controls before boarding the train in Brussels, but would remain on the train after Lille/Calais and continue to the UK, thereby leaving the Schengen Area and entering the UK without having undergone the proper border checks. A number of passengers were able to travel to the UK and claim asylum on arrival in the UK using this method.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/546809/An-Inspection-of-Juxtaposed-Controls_Aug_2013.pdf |title=An Inspection of Juxtaposed Controls (November 2012 - March 2013) |publisher=[[Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration]] |date=8 August 2013 |access-date=28 March 2020 |at=paras 4.3-4.4}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=8 December 2011 |title=Tighter checks pledged to close Eurostar 'loophole' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-16092647 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter this loophole came to light in December 2011, Eurostar initially suspended the sale of point to point Brussels to Lille/Calais tickets, while maintaining the sale of season tickets on this route. Subsequently, Eurostar resumed the sale of tickets, but restricted the sale of Brussels-Lille/Calais tickets to 3 daily services. Upon arrival at Lille, the number of Brussels-Lille tickets sold were reconciled with the total number of disembarkations. Security guards conducted ticket inspections on passengers before the trains arrived at Calais, where those without a valid ticket to the UK would be instructed to disembark. In addition to the pre-embarkation juxtaposed controls, the UK Border Force also checked the travel documents of passengers travelling on these 3 services on arrival at London St Pancras International station.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmhaff/71/71.pdf |title=The work of the UK Border Agency (December 2011\u2013March 2012) |publisher=[[House of Commons]] [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] |at=Ev 61 |date=16 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Lords/2012-04-23/debates/1204237000932/ImmigrationEurostar |title=House of Lords Hansard for 23 April 2012, Volume 736 (Immigration: Eurostar) |publisher=[[House of Lords]]}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Belgium and the UK signed an agreement clarifying that at the juxtaposed controls in Brussels-South station, 'Immigration controls performed by the United Kingdom are only permitted on passengers whose travel destination is stated to be within the United Kingdom'. Further, 'Where a person who on Belgium territory boarded an international train using the Fixed Link and has arrived in the United Kingdom is refused entry, having been found to have avoided United Kingdom immigration controls on Belgian territory by stating that their final destination is intra-Schengen, the authorities of Belgium may not refuse to accept such a person for readmittance'. The agreement entered into force on 1 October 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/558195/TS_32_2016_CM_9339_Channel_WEB.pdf |title=Agreement between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Nothern Ireland and the Government of the Kingdom of Belgium, concerning Immigration Controls on Rail Traffic between Belgium and the United Kingdom using the Channel Fixed Link |publisher=HM Government |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn order to close this loophole, passengers travelling from Brussels to Lille or Calais go through a different departure area in [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussels-South]] station (bypassing the juxtaposed controls for passengers heading to the UK) and travel in a separate designated coach (available in standard class only) controlled by security guards, who ensure that all of these passengers disembark at Lille/Calais before the train goes on to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurostar.com/uk-en/conditions-carriage |title=Conditions of Carriage |date=4 February 2019 |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327221758/https://www.eurostar.com/uk-en/conditions-carriage |archive-date=27 March 2020 |quote=For security and border control reasons, any booking for intra-Schengen travel from Brussels to Lille or Calais is available in Standard class only and limited to coach 18 or 16 (the \u201cDedicated Coach\u201d), depending on the type of train. Intra-Schengen passengers departing from Brussels are not subject to border controls, whether for exiting Schengen area or entering the United Kingdom. Therefore, any movement by any intra-Schengen passenger to and from the Dedicated Coach between Brussels and Lille or Calais will be strictly limited and controlled. You must cooperate with our on-board staff and agents, as well as security and border control authorities in the stations in relation to these requirements. Any failure to cooperate, any non-authorised movement to and from the Dedicated Coach and/or any refusal from any intra-Schengen passenger to get off the train at Lille or Calais may result in the intervention of security and border authorities}}</ref> Until 30 January 2017, regular commuters holding a season ticket were exempt from this measure due to the high number of travellers on peak-hour services.<ref>{{cite news |last=Pyman |first=Tom |date=23 January 2017 |title=Charlie Elphicke calls on home secretary Amber Rudd to end \u2018Lille Loophole\u2019 which allows unchecked arrivals in Kent from Europe |url=https://www.gravesendreporter.co.uk/news/charlie-elphicke-calls-on-home-secretary-amber-rudd-to-end-lille-loophole-which-allows-unchecked-arrivals-in-kent-from-europe-1-4859787 |work=Gravesend Reporter |access-date=28 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328140556/https://www.gravesendreporter.co.uk/news/charlie-elphicke-calls-on-home-secretary-amber-rudd-to-end-lille-loophole-which-allows-unchecked-arrivals-in-kent-from-europe-1-4859787 |archive-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> After this exemption was removed, regular commuters complained that only one coach (with 48 seats and standing capacity for 20 people) was allocated for passengers from Brussels to Lille on the peak hour train service departing from Brussels at 17:56.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tymen |first=Elodie |date=27 January 2017 |title=Eurostar : Londres impose des quotas pour les voyageurs entre Bruxelles et Lille |url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/societes/2017/01/27/20005-20170127ARTFIG00166-eurostar-londres-impose-des-quotas-pour-les-voyageurs-non-britanniques.php |work=[[Le Figaro]] |language=French |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Aballain |first=Olivier |date=26 January 2017 |title=UE : Comment les Anglais d\u00e9cident du sort d\u2019un train Bruxelles-Lille |url=https://www.20minutes.fr/lille/2003551-20170126-ue-comment-anglais-decident-sort-train-bruxelles-lille |work=[[20 minutes (France)]] |language=French |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===List of railway stations with juxtaposed controls===\n;In Belgium<ref>{{cite web|url=http://publications.europa.eu/resource/cellar/8ec06bfe-f76c-479b-a230-7dcd9af53966.0006.02/DOC_1|title=Update of the list of border crossing points referred to in Article 2(8) of Regulation (EC) No 562/2006 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 15 March 2006 establishing a Community Code on the rules governing the movement of persons across borders (Schengen Borders Code) (2007/C 316/01) |date=28 December 2007 |publisher=European Council }}</ref>\n* [[Brussels-South railway station|Brussel-Zuid/Bruxelles-Midi]]\n;In France<ref name=\"FRbordercrossingpoints\">{{cite web|url=https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=uriserv:OJ.C_.2020.064.01.0017.01.ENG&toc=OJ:C:2020:064:FULL |title=Update of the list of border crossing points as referred to in Article 2(8) of Regulation (EU) 2016/399 of the European Parliament and of the Council on a Union Code on the rules governing the movement of persons across borders (Schengen Borders Code) (2020/C 64/06) |date=27 February 2020 |publisher=European Council}}</ref>\n* [[Gare de Bourg-Saint-Maurice|Bourg-Saint-Maurice]]\n* [[Gare de Calais-Fr\u00e9thun|Calais\u2013Fr\u00e9thun]]\n* [[Eurotunnel Calais Terminal]] in [[Coquelles]]\n* [[Gare de Lille-Europe|Lille Europe]]\n* [[Gare de Mo\u00fbtiers-Salins-Brides-les-Bains|Mo\u00fbtiers\u2013Salins\u2013Brides-les-Bains]]\n* [[Gare du Nord|Paris Nord]]\n;In the Netherlands \n* [[Amsterdam Centraal]] (starting from 30 April 2020)<ref name=\"Amsterdam2020\"/><ref name=\"EurostarNL2020\"/>\n* [[Rotterdam Centraal]] (starting from 18 May 2020)<ref name=\"EurostarNL2020\"/>\n;In the UK<ref name=\"FRbordercrossingpoints\"/>\n* [[Eurotunnel Folkestone Terminal]] in [[Cheriton, Kent]]\n* [[Ashford International railway station|Ashford International]]\n* [[Ebbsfleet International railway station|Ebbsfleet International]]\n* [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras International]]\n\n==Ferry==\n[[File:UK border control in the ferry area of the Port of Dunkerque-3749.jpg|thumb|right|300px|[[UK Border Force]] checkpoint in the Port of Dunkirk, where immigration checks are carried out before boarding the ferry to Dover.]]\nOn 4 February 2003, France and the UK concluded the '''Treaty of Le Touquet''' (formally known as the ''Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom and the Government of the French Republic concerning the implementation of frontier controls at sea ports of both countries on the Channel and North Sea'').<ref name=\"ukto\">{{cite web|title=Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the French Republic concerning the Implementation of Frontier Controls at the Sea Ports of both countries on the Channel and North Sea|url=http://treaties.fco.gov.uk/treaties/treatyrecord.htm?tid=8012|website=UK Treaties Online|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"french-law\">{{cite web|title=Approbation du trait\u00e9 entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la mise en oeuvre de contr\u00f4les frontaliers dans les ports maritimes de la Manche et de la mer du Nord|url=http://www.senat.fr/leg/pjl02-433.html|website=S\u00e9nat|accessdate=5 July 2016|language=French}}</ref><ref name=\"channel4-copy-law\">{{cite web|title=Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom and the Government of the French Republic concerning the implementation of frontier controls at sea ports of both countries on the Channel and North Sea|url=http://blogs.channel4.com/factcheck/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2016/02/LeTouquetTreaty2003.pdf|website=Channel 4|accessdate=5 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420152543/http://blogs.channel4.com/factcheck/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2016/02/LeTouquetTreaty2003.pdf|archive-date=20 April 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> This agreement provided for juxtaposed controls on a number of cross-Channel ferry routes. The Treaty was subsequently put into effect in France by Law No. 2003-1368 of 31 December 2003<ref>{{cite French law|number or usual name=n\u00b0 2003-1368 |date in French=31 d\u00e9cembre 2003 |full name=autorisant l'approbation du trait\u00e9 entre le Gouvernement de la R\u00e9publique fran\u00e7aise et le Gouvernement du Royaume-Uni de Grande-Bretagne et d'Irlande du Nord relatif \u00e0 la mise en oeuvre de contr\u00f4les frontaliers dans les ports maritimes de la Manche et de la mer du Nord des deux pays |language=French |URL=https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000609921}}</ref> and in the UK by the [[Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002 (Juxtaposed Controls) Order 2003]], under the authority of the [[Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002]].<ref name=\"2003 order\">{{Cite legislation UK |type=si |year=2003 |number=2818 |si=The Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002 (Juxtaposed Controls) Order 2003}}</ref>\n\nFrance has established immigration checkpoints at the [[Port of Dover]], where the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] carries out immigration entry checks into the [[Schengen Area]] on passengers travelling to [[Calais]] or [[Dunkirk]]. French Border Police officers have the power to carry firearms and to arrest and detain individuals in the immigration control zone in the Port of Dover.<ref name=\"2003 order\"/> On the other hand, the [[UK Border Force]] does not carry out routine exit checks at the Port of Dover. Instead, since April 2015, the ferry operator collects passengers' travel document information during the booking or check-in process, which it sends electronically to the UK Border Force. However, coaches carrying organised school groups (consisting of students aged 16 and under accompanied by teachers or other responsible adults) are exempt from having their travel document information collected and sent to the UK Border Force.<ref name=\"Exit Checks\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doverport.co.uk/about/news/introduction-of-government-imposed-exit-checks-at/12953/ |title=Introduction of Government-imposed Exit Checks at Port of Dover |publisher=[[Port of Dover]] |date=12 March 2015 |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411041133/https://www.doverport.co.uk/about/news/introduction-of-government-imposed-exit-checks-at/12953/ |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt present, the UK has immigration checkpoints at the ports of [[Port of Calais|Calais]] and Dunkirk (previously, the UK also had an immigration checkpoint at the port of [[Boulogne-sur-Mer]]). UK Border Force officers have the power to arrest and detain individuals in the immigration control zone in the ports of Calais and Dunkirk.<ref name=\"2003 order\"/> Passengers travelling from Calais and Dunkirk to the UK go through French exit checks as well as UK immigration entry checks before embarkation.\n\nCustoms checks on ferry passengers remain unaffected by the Treaty and continue to take place upon arrival after leaving the ferry. Therefore, when travelling from France to [[Dover]], although ferry passengers have already gone through immigration checks before departure, when they arrive in the UK, they might still be stopped by customs officers for a customs inspection. Similarly, when travelling from Dover to France, although ferry passengers have already been through immigration checks by the French Border Police at Dover, they might still be subject to a customs check by [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|French Customs]] on arrival in France.<ref name=\"InspectionReport4.2\"/>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2007, 10,766 people were refused entry into the UK by UK immigration officers stationed in Calais.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200708/ldselect/ldeucom/60/60we05.htm|title=Written evidence by the Home Office Border Controls at Calais and Coquelles |date=16 January 2008 |publisher=[[House of Lords]] [[European Union Committee]]}}</ref>\n\nA Joint Operational Coordination Centre has been created at the Port of Calais to strengthen co-operation between the [[UK Border Force]], [[French Border Police]] and [[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|French Customs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/257276/declaration.pdf |title=UK-France Summit, 2 November 2010 \u2013 Declaration on Immigration |publisher=HM Government}}</ref>\n\nSince 2011, private security officers employed by Eamus Cork Solutions (ECS) work in the freight lanes at the juxtaposed controls at the Port of Calais and the Port of Dunkirk. Their job is to detect people concealed inside vehicles attempting to enter the UK through visual inspections, sniffer dogs, or by equipment including heartbeat monitors, carbon dioxide detectors and scanners.<ref name=\"Bosworth\">{{cite journal |last=Bosworth |first=Mary |date= |title=Immigration detention and juxtaposed border controls on the French north coast |url=https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:7058db27-e9dc-4385-b35e-8e10ae96cfa1/download_file?file_format=pdf&safe_filename=calais_revised_31.10.19.pdf&type_of_work=Journal+article |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411140650/https://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:7058db27-e9dc-4385-b35e-8e10ae96cfa1/download_file?file_format=pdf&safe_filename=calais_revised_31.10.19.pdf&type_of_work=Journal+article |journal=European Journal of Criminology |access-date=11 April 2020 |archive-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=19 September 2016 |title=Home Office prepared to pay up to \u00a380m for French port security |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-37411314 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the UK-France Summit held at the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] on 18 January 2018, [[President of France|French President]] [[Emmanuel Macron]] and [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|UK Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] announced that the UK would provide an additional \u20ac50 million in financial support for 2018 for France to strengthen border security (including fencing, CCTV and detection technology) at the juxtaposed controls at the Port of Calais, as well as to establish accommodation facilities located outside the Calais and Dunkirk areas, such as Reception and Assessment Centres.<ref>{{cite web|title=United Kingdom-France Summit Communique |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/674880/2018_UK-FR_Summit_Communique.pdf |date=18 January 2018 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> The two countries also agreed to a treaty (known as the '''Sandhurst Treaty''')<ref name=\"HL Paper 428\"/> with provisions to implement the [[Dublin III Regulation]] concerning the treatment of unaccompanied asylum seeking children and to establish a Joint Information and Coordination Centre (in French: Centre Conjoint d\u2019Information et de Coordination, or CCIC). The Sandhurst Treaty entered into force on 1 February 2018,<ref>{{cite web|title=Treaty between the Government of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland and the Government of the French Republic Concerning the Reinforcement of Cooperation for the Coordinated Management of their Shared Border |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/678596/TS01.2018_Cm9568_UK_France_Shared_Border_WEB.pdf |date=18 January 2018 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> and the Joint Centre became operational on 23 November 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Joint UK-France centre opens in Calais to tackle criminality at border |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/joint-uk-france-centre-opens-in-calais-to-tackle-criminality-at-border |date=27 November 2018 |website=Gov.uk |publisher=HM Government |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Minister of the Interior (France)|French Minister of the Interior]], [[Christophe Castaner]], has stated that if the juxtaposed controls were removed, it would lead to increased waiting times for travellers to clear immigration and customs on arrival.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doubles contr\u00f4les douaniers \u00e0 Calais |url=https://www.senat.fr/questions/base/2019/qSEQ190309586.html |date=18 April 2019 |publisher=[[Senate (France)]] |language=fr |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Her Majesty's Chief Inspector of Prisons]], [[Peter Clarke (police officer)|Peter Clarke]], carried out an unannounced inspection of the UK's short-term holding facility (STHF) at the Port of Calais, which is managed by private contractor [[Mitie]]. The Chief Inspector raised concerns about the routine practice of detaining people in caged escort vehicles that were in 'appalling condition, with ripped out seats' for 'prolonged periods' while awaiting the arrival of the French Border Police. Few of the detainees were interviewed and UK Border Force officers could not state the legal authority under which these detainees were held. Detainees refused entry to the UK would be handed to the French Border Police and then be released outside the port area.<ref name=\"Prisons Inspector 2019 Report\"/><ref name=\"ITV 2020\"/> No onsite medical care or access to legal advice is provided in the STHF.<ref name=\"Bosworth\"/>\n\nUK Border Force officers and Detainee Custody Officers (DCOs) employed by [[Mitie]] who work at the juxtaposed controls are either bussed in daily across the Channel from their homes in [[Kent]], or they reside four nights a week in a hotel in Calais.<ref name=\"Bosworth\"/>\n\n==Air==\nThere are no juxtaposed controls on cross-Channel air travel. Air carriers are required under UK and Schengen rules to perform checks before boarding that passengers possess travel documents to enter the destination country.<ref>{{Cite legislation UK | type = act | year = 1999 | chapter = 33 | act = Immigration and Asylum Act | section = 40}}</ref><ref>[https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/en/ALL/?uri=celex%3A42000A0922%2802%29 Schengen Convention], Article 26(1)(b)</ref><ref>[https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/ALL/?uri=uriserv%3AOJ.L_.2001.187.01.0045.01.ENG Council Directive 2001/51/EC of 28 June 2001 supplementing the provisions of Article 26 of the Convention implementing the Schengen Agreement of 14 June 1985 (Carriers Liability Directive)]</ref> Passengers flying from the [[Schengen Area]] to the UK undergo Schengen exit checks at the departure airport and entry checks by the [[UK Border Force]] at the arrival airport in the UK. For passengers flying from the UK to the Schengen Area, the UK Border Force does not conduct routine exit checks. Instead, the air carrier takes passengers' travel document information during the check-in process, which is transmitted electronically to the UK Border Force.<ref name=\"Exit Checks\"/> Passengers then go through Schengen entry immigration and customs checks on arrival in the Schengen Area.\n\n==Implications of the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union==\nThe [[House of Lords]] [[European Union Committee]] has observed that the Treaty of Le Touquet led to a 'build-up of pressure in the Calais region of people who seek to come to the UK but who do not fulfil immigration requirements and are unable to seek asylum in the UK from France', and that the 'continuous establishment of unregulated camp sites for people in this position is an irritant in French politics'. As a consequence, after the result of the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum]], there were increased calls in France to scrap the Treaty of Le Touquet and end juxtaposed controls, including from the then French Presidential candidates [[Alain Jupp\u00e9]] and [[Emmanuel Macron]], and from the [[List of the mayors of Calais|Mayor of Calais]], [[Natacha Bouchart]]. However, such calls have since receded, as political leaders in France and the UK have sought to reinforce their commitment to bilateral border cooperation (for example, by entering into the Sandhurst Treaty). At the same time, the Committee has noted that although the agreements establishing juxtaposed controls are 'not formally EU-dependent, the agreements underpinning bilateral border cooperation have undoubtedly been easier to sustain under the shared umbrella of EU membership'.<ref name=\"HL Paper 428\">{{cite web|title=48th Report of Session 2017\u201319 - Brexit: refugee protection and asylum policy (HL Paper 428) |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201719/ldselect/ldeucom/428/42806.htm#footnote-124-backlink |date=11 October 2019 |publisher=[[House of Lords]] [[European Union Committee]] |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, the United Kingdom [[Brexit|ceased to be a member state of the European Union]]. During the transiton period that is set to end on 31 December 2020, the arrangements for juxtaposed controls remain unchanged.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eurostar.com/rw-en/brexit |title=Eurostar and Brexit |publisher=[[Eurostar]] |access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:France LFT Londres passport stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Entry stamp]] into the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras International]] station. ('LFT' stands for 'Liaison fixe transmanche' (literally: cross-Channel fixed link))\nFile:France BCNJ Douvres.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Entry stamp]] into the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at the [[Port of Dover]]. ('BCNJ' stands for 'Bureaux \u00e0 contr\u00f4les nationaux juxtapos\u00e9s' (literally: juxtaposed national countrol booths))\nFile:Brussels Zuid Midi Station passport stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Exit stamp]] from the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Belgian Federal Police]] at [[Brussels-South railway station]].\nFile:France LFT Lille Europe stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Exit stamp]] from the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at [[Lille Europe]] station. ('LFT' stands for 'Liaison fixe transmanche' (literally: cross-Channel fixed link))\nFile:France LFT Paris Nord passport stamp.jpg|[[Passport stamp#Schengen Area|Exit stamp]] from the [[Schengen Area]] issued by the [[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|French Border Police]] at [[Paris Gare du Nord]] station. ('LFT' stands for 'Liaison fixe transmanche' (literally: cross-Channel fixed link))\nFile:USA Passport Channel Tunnel and Gare du Nord.jpg|Pair of passport stamps (exit from France, entry into the UK) at the juxtaposed border controls at [[Paris Gare du Nord]] station.\nFile:UKE HENSLEY.JPG|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Force]] at [[Paris Gare du Nord]] station.\nFile:UK Frethun passport stamp.jpg|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Agency]] at [[Calais-Fr\u00e9thun]] station.\nFile:UK Calais passport stamp.jpg|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Force]] at the [[Port of Calais]].\nFile:UK Brussels passport stamp.jpg|British [[Passport stamp#United Kingdom|entry stamp]] issued by the [[UK Border Agency]] at [[Brussels-South railway station]].\n</gallery>\n\n==Juxtaposed controls at other borders==\nApart from the borders along the English Channel, juxtaposed border controls or similar arrangements exist in other countries:\n*[[United States border preclearance]] (a similar arrangement whereby the US carries out pre-embarkation immigration checks at some airports and border crossing points in Canada, the Caribbean, Ireland, and the United Arab Emirates)\n*[[Shenzhen Bay Control Point]] (a similar arrangement whereby Hong Kong carries out immigration checks at the border crossing point geographically located in the [[Mainland China|Mainland]], but the area is designated as if it is part of Hong Kong and Hong Kong law fully applies)\n*[[West Kowloon railway station]] [[West Kowloon Station Mainland Port Area|control point]]<ref>[http://gia.info.gov.hk/general/201707/25/P2017072500891_264072_1_1500987862639.pdf Press Conference on the Co-location Arrangement of the Hong Kong Section of the Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link] </ref> ([[Bill (law)|bill]] introduced to the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]] in early 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201801/17/P2018011700514.htm|title=LCQ4: Co-location Arrangement of Hong Kong Section of Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link|website=www.info.gov.hk}}</ref><ref>[https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr17-18/english/bc/bc102/general/bc102.htm Bills Committee on Guangzhou-Shenzhen-Hong Kong Express Rail Link (Co-location) Bill]</ref> passed on 14 June 2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/2150873/hong-kongs-controversial-china-rail-checkpoint-bill-finally|title=Hong Kong\u2019s controversial China rail checkpoint bill finally passed|date=14 June 2018|website=[[South China Morning Post]]}}</ref>\n*[[Woodlands Train Checkpoint]] (a similar arrangement where passengers undergo Malaysian entry formalities at the station, despite it being located in Singaporean territory)\n*[[Padang Besar railway station]] in [[Padang Besar, Malaysia]] which houses CIQ facilities for both [[Malaysia]] and [[Thailand]] despite being wholly within Malaysia territory.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.malaysiatrains.com/padang-besar-railway-station-train-times-tickets/ | title=Padang Besar Railway Station \u2013 Train times & tickets| publisher=Malaysia Trains|language=English|accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Princess Juliana International Airport]], [[Sint Maarten]] and [[Grand Case-Esp\u00e9rance Airport]], [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]] (where there are joint border controls pursuant to the [[Franco-Dutch treaty on Saint Martin border controls]])\n\n==See also==\n*[[Migrants around Calais]]\n*[[List of border crossing points in France]]\n*[[Belgian Federal Police]]\n*[[Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res|Direction centrale de la police aux fronti\u00e8res (French Border Police)]]\n*[[Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes|Directorate-General of Customs and Indirect Taxes (French Customs)]]\n*[[Royal Marechaussee|Royal Marechaussee (The Netherlands)]]\n*[[UK Border Force]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Ryan, Bernard. ''Extraterritorial Immigration Control: Legal Challenges''. [[Martinus Nijhoff Publishers]], 2010, pp.&nbsp;16\u201319\n\n[[Category:International border crossings]]\n[[Category:Border crossings of France]]\n[[Category:International travel documents]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement in Europe]]\n[[Category:Transport and the European Union]]\n[[Category:Calais migrant crisis (1999\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Border crossings of Belgium]]\n[[Category:Border crossings of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Juxtaposed border controls]]\n", "name_user": "Brandon5485", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eImplications of the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union:spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juxtaposed_controls"}
